# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cherbourg
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The **1986 Tour de France** was a cycling race held in France, from 4 July to 27 July.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] It was the 73rd running of the Tour de France.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Greg LeMond of La Vie Claire won the race, ahead of his teammate Bernard Hinault.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] It was the first ever victory for a rider outside of Europe.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Five-time Tour winner Hinault, who had won the year before with LeMond supporting him, had publicly pledged to ride in support of LeMond in 1986.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Several attacks during the race cast doubt on the sincerity of his promise, leading to a rift between the two riders and the entire La Vie Claire team.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The 1986 Tour de France is widely considered to be one of the most memorable in the history of the sport due to the battle between LeMond and Hinault.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Thierry Marie (Système U) took the first race leader's yellow jersey after winning the prologue time trial.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The lead then moved to Alex Stieda (7-Eleven) after stage 1, only for Marie to recapture the lead after his team won the team time trial on stage 2.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] After short stints in the lead for Dominique Gaigne and Johan van der Velde, Jørgen V.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Pedersen took the yellow jersey following a breakaway on stage 7 and retained the lead even after the first long time trial, won by Hinault.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Stage 12 saw Hinault attack with Pedro Delgado (PDM–Ultima–Concorde), who won the stage, while Hinault moved into the lead.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Hinault attacked again the following day, but was caught and dropped.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] LeMond gained back significant time, but still trailed his teammate by 40 seconds.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] LeMond would move into the yellow jersey after stage 17, when Hinault fell behind on the climb of the Col d'Izoard.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Stage 18 to Alpe d'Huez saw LeMond and Hinault finish hand-in-hand, with the latter winning the stage.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] LeMond's overall victory was sealed when Hinault was unable to overcome his deficit in the final time trial on stage 20.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Urs Zimmermann (Carrera Jeans–Vagabond) finished third, and was the only rider who posed a threat to the La Vie Claire team, who also had the 4th placed rider in Andy Hampsten.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] In the race's other classifications, Hinault won the mountains classification, Panasonic–Merckx–Agu rider Eric Vanderaerden the points classification, and La Vie Claire's Andrew Hampsten won the young rider classification.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] La Vie Claire finished at the head of the team classification by one hour 51 minutes, after placing four riders inside the final overall top-ten placings.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] One of cycling's Grand Tours, the Tour consisted of 23 stages, beginning with a prologue in Boulogne-Billancourt and concluded on the Champs-Élysées in Paris.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The race was organised by the Amaury Sport Organisation and was shown on television in 72 countries, with the total viewers estimated at one billion.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] In June, 23 teams had requested to start in the 1986 Tour.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The Tour organisers, Amaury Sport Organisation (ASO), accepted 21 applications, so a total of 21 teams participated in the 1986 Tour de France.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The two teams whose application was denied were Skala-Skil and Miko.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Each team sent a squad of ten riders, which meant that the race would start with a peloton of 210 cyclists, a record setting total.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The ASO felt that 210 starters were too many and moved to reduce the size of the squads to eight riders each, but the teams protested, and the original number remained.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] 7-Eleven became the Tour's first team from the United States, with a squad consisting of eight Americans, one Canadian and one Mexican.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Jim Ochowicz, 7-Eleven's founder and manager, met with the ASO and persuaded them to invite his team.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] In the Spring, the team withdrew from competition in Europe (missing the opportunity to become the first American team in the history of the Vuelta a España) due to the United States conflict with Libya, losing out on much needed competitive racing unavailable in the United States.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Joop Zoetemelk, the reigning road world champion, started and finished his 16th Tour de France, a record that stood until it was tied by Sylvain Chavanel in 2018.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] , the eventual winner, were considered among the favourites to win before the race.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Five-time Tour winner and defending champion Bernard Hinault (La Vie Claire) had promised to support his teammate Greg LeMond, who had finished second in 1985, following controversy during that race when LeMond felt that a chance of potential victory had been taken from him due to team tactics.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] La Vie Claire was therefore considered the squad to beat, with the team also featuring strong riders such as Andrew Hampsten, who had won the Tour de Suisse several weeks before the Tour de France.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Before the start of the event, Hinault announced it would be the last Tour de France of his career.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Prior to the start of the Tour, LeMond was confident of his chances, and pointed out that having Hinault, who he expected to take an early lead, would play to his advantage.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Even with Hinault's assurances of support for LeMond, excitement over a possible record-breaking sixth Tour win was high in France.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] In a survey of 15 Dutch journalists, eight named Hinault as their main favourite for overall victory, just three chose LeMond.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] LeMond's season up to this point had been good, but had not yielded any major victories; he finished second at Milan–San Remo, third at Paris–Nice, fourth at the Giro d'Italia and third at the Tour de Suisse.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Laurent Fignon (Système U), winner in 1983 and 1984, was working on his comeback, having won the La Flèche Wallonne classic in the spring.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] He had missed the chance to defend his title the year earlier due to surgery on an inflamed Achilles tendon.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Juan Mora of *El País* believed that the race would be highlighted by a duel between Fignon and Hinault.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] He named LeMond and Frenchman Charly Mottet as potential contenders if their team captains – Hinault and Fignon, respectively – failed to perform to the level expected.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Mora believed Pedro Delgado to be the best Spanish contender for the overall title citing that his PDM–Ultima–Concorde should perform well in the team time trial.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Gian Paolo Ormezzano of *La Stampa* believed that there was no Italian rider competing that could be a legitimate threat to win the race, despite the fact that three Italian based teams were invited – the most since the 1979 edition.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Ormezzano also thought the favourites going into the race were Hinault and Fignon.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Five-time Tour winner Jacques Anquetil named Luis Herrera (Café de Colombia–Varta) as his main favourite.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Sean Kelly (Kas) was considered the main favourite for victory in the points classification, having won the trophy a record-equalling third time the year before.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] However, a crash on the last stage of the Tour de Suisse prevented Kelly from starting.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] In his absence, Adri van der Poel (Kwantum–Decosol–Yoko) was given the best chances to win the classification.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The race route for the 1986 edition of the Tour de France was unveiled on 8 October 1985 by both Jacques Goddet and Félix Lévitan.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The race was pushed back a week from its normal date in order to prevent overlap with the 1986 FIFA World Cup, and therefore started on 4 July.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Covering a total of 4,094 km (2,544 mi), it included four time trials (three individual and one for teams) and ten stages deemed as flat.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The race included four stages that featured a summit finish: stage 13 to Superbagnères; stage 17 to Col du Granon; stage 18 to Alpe d'Huez; and stage 21 to Puy de Dôme.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The race took a counter-clockwise route around France.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Following the prologue and opening stages in the Hauts-de-Seine region, the race moved north towards the Belgian border, before turning west to Brittany.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The Tour then traveled south to Bordeaux, where a train transfer brought the riders to Bayonne, at the foot of the Pyrenees.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] From there, transition stages led the race to the Alps, before the final stages in the Massif Central and further north towards Paris.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The 1986 Tour de France had one rest day, after the finish on the Alpe d'Huez.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The highest point of elevation in the race was 2,642 m (8,668 ft) at the summit of the Col du Galibier mountain pass on stage 18.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The longest road-race stage was stage 11, at 258.3 km (160.5 mi).
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Tour director Levitan felt after the 1985 Tour de France that the race had been too easy, and made the course in 1986 extra difficult, including more mountain climbs than before.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] This angered Hinault, who threatened to skip the 1986 Tour.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Before the race started, an avalanche deposited a large amount of dirt and rock on the slopes of the Col du Tourmalet, prompting Goddet to consider rerouting the course through the Col d'Aubisque.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The prologue was won by Thierry Marie (Système U), with Hinault in third place, just two seconds slower.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Fignon and LeMond placed seventh and eighth, both four seconds back.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] On stage 1, Alex Stieda (7-Eleven) attacked 40 km (25 mi) from the finish and collected time bonuses at the intermediate sprint, which would move him into the race lead.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] He was then joined in his breakaway by five other riders.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The sextet held a small margin until the finish, with Pol Verschuere (Fagor) taking the victory.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Stieda, a Canadian, became the first rider from North America to wear the race leader's yellow jersey.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The same afternoon, the team time trial was held.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The attempt at defending Stieda's race lead by his 7-Eleven team proved unsuccessful.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] A crash by Eric Heiden slowed the team and forced several riders to take evasive action in order not to run into him, in the process scraping their tyres at the street curbing, which caused several punctures.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] In addition, Stieda was tired by his morning effort and fell back, getting in danger of missing the time limit.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Chris Carmichael and Jeff Pierce had to fall back to lead him to the finish, which he reached in time but the yellow jersey was lost.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] It was regained by Marie, whose Système U team won the time trial, while La Vie Claire lost almost two minutes.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Hinault personally instructed the team to wait for Niki Rüttimann and Guido Winterberg, who were nursing the after-effects of crashes during the morning stage, accounting for La Vie Claire's comparatively poor performance.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Café de Colombia–Varta lost significant time and four of the team's riders were eliminated because they missed the time limit.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] 7-Eleven bounced back from their disappointment the following day, with Davis Phinney becoming the first American to win a road race stage.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Phinney won the stage from a bunch sprint, even though he had been in the day's breakaway for most of the stage.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Stage 4 went through Normandy, on rolling terrain.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Régis Simon (RMO–Cycles Méral–Mavic) broke away from the peloton and at 80 km (50 mi) from the finish, he held a lead of over ten minutes.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] He was eventually caught by a counterattack from Federico Echave (Teka).
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] On the finishing straight, Pello Ruiz Cabestany (Seat–Orbea) overtook Echave to win the stage.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Dutch champion Jos Lammertink (Panasonic–Merckx–Agu) retired after suffering a broken skull in a crash, while Fabio Parra (Café de Colombia–Varta) also dropped out, courtesy of knee problems, leaving his team with only five of their original ten starters.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Dominique Gaigne took over the yellow jersey from his teammate Marie, who he now led by six seconds.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Johan van der Velde (Panasonic–Merckx–Agu) won stage 5 and through time bonuses at both intermediate sprints and the stage finish, moved into the overall lead.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] He got the better of Joël Pelier (Kas) at the finish line.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Both had been in a breakaway together, started after 16 km (9.9 mi) ridden.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] They finished 39 seconds ahead of van der Velde's teammate Eddy Planckaert, who in turn was followed by Miguel Induráin (Reynolds), while the field, led by Alfonso Gutiérrez (Teka), was 1:15 minutes behind.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The stage saw a demonstration by workers in Lisieux, which did not impede the race.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Van der Velde kept the race lead the following day.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] A five-man breakaway decided the outcome of the stage, won by Guido Bontempi of Carrera Jeans–Vagabond ahead of Roberto Pagnin (Malvor–Bottecchia–Sidi).
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The yellow jersey changed hands again after stage 7.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The stage began slowly, with the first breakaway established only after 105 km (65 mi).
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The peloton was back together after 150 km (93 mi), but another attack went shortly thereafter, including Ludo Peeters (Kwantum–Decosol–Yoko), Jørgen V.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Pedersen (Carrera Jeans–Vagabond), and Induráin.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Other riders joined them 20 km (12 mi) later, but it was Peeters who eventually won the sprint from the group to win the stage, ahead of Ron Kiefel (7-Eleven).
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] On stage 8, after 70 km (43 mi) the peloton allowed Yvon Madiot (Système U) to drive ahead of the field to greet his family.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Planckaert, not realising the situation, followed what he considered an attack in the company of Pelier, but all three were brought back.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] About 20 km (12 mi) later, another group broke away, containing Adri van der Poel (Kwantum–Decosol–Yoko), Mathieu Hermans, (Seat–Orbea) and Andrew Hampsten.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Hampsten was considered a threat to the overall classification, which led the field to give chase.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The peloton was united before their arrival in the finishing town, Nantes, where Silvano Contini (Gis Gelati) launched an unsuccessful breakaway attempt.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Planckert, who only started the stage with the help of analgesic pills from his masseur due to back pain, won the sprint, beating out his teammate Eric Vanderaerden.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The first real test for the general classification contenders came on stage 9, a 61.5 km (38.2 mi) individual time trial around Nantes.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Hinault won the stage, 44 seconds ahead of LeMond, with Roche third, 1:01 minutes slower.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Hinault benefited from a puncture by LeMond, which cost him time.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Fignon finished in 32nd place, 3:42 minutes behind Hinault, a result he later described as "unworthy of my status".
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Pedersen did enough to retain the yellow jersey.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Roche moved into second place, 1:05 minutes behind Pedersen, with Hinault a further five seconds behind in third.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] LeMond was eighth, 1:59 minutes behind the lead.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Stage 10 was won by Ángel Sarrapio (Teka), who had been in a breakaway with Jean-Claude Bagot (Fagor) during the stage.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Pedersen kept the race lead, while Pelier used bonus seconds on the road to move ahead of Roche into second place in the general classification.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] On stage 11, a 12-man breakaway reached the finishing town of Bordeaux together.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Rudy Dhaenens (Hitachi–Robland) escaped from the group 5 km (3.1 mi) from the finish.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] On the finishing straight, he was almost caught by the fast approaching Hermans and just held on to take the stage victory.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Hermans would later say that the public announcer had aided Dhaenens' victory by warning him of Hermans over the PA system.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Following a train transfer from Bordeaux to Bayonne at the foot of the Pyrenees in the morning, stage 12 led the riders over 217 km (135 mi) to Pau.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The stage featured five mountain passes, with the first-category rated Col de Marie-Blanque at the end, before a descent into the finishing town.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Several attacks occurred over the first part of the stage, each covered by riders of La Vie Claire.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] At around 90 km (56 mi) from the finish, Hinault raised the pace on the ascent of the Col de Burdincurutcheta, forcing other contenders to chase back on, such as Herrera.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Others, such as Roche, Fignon, and race leader Pedersen, dropped behind and would lose a lot of time by the end of the stage.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Shortly before an intermediate sprint after 125 km (78 mi), Hinault told his teammate Jean-François Bernard to accelerate, and the two, accompanied by Delgado, made the bridge to a lead group containing Eduardo Chozas (Teka).
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] These four riders then broke clear at the front, before Chozas lost contact about 25 km (16 mi) later.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Bernard, the work for his team leader done, fell back another 15 km (9.3 mi) down the road.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Delgado and Hinault worked well together to extend their advantage to the chasers, where LeMond, bound by team tactics, was unable to give chase himself.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] According to Delgado, Hinault clearly wanted to make time for the overall classification, and without any negotiating between the two, he gifted the stage win to Delgado.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] LeMond managed to break clear of the rest of the chase group with Herrera, but still arrived in Pau 4:37 minutes behind Hinault, who was now leading the race overall.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] After the stage, LeMond was overheard telling his father: "Goddamnit, Dad, I am going to finish second again!" Other favourites lost even more time: Robert Millar (Panasonic–Merckx–Agu) finished 11th, 5:31 minutes behind.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] In 20th place was Fignon, arriving 11 minutes after Hinault.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Roche lost 21 minutes, Phil Anderson (Panasonic–Merckx–Agu) 33 minutes.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Stage 13 led the race through the Pyrenees again, over 186 km (116 mi) and four high mountain passes.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The first was the Col du Tourmalet, coming after 75 km (47 mi), followed by the Col d'Aspin, the Col de Peyresourde, and the final climb up to the ski resort of Superbagnères.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Laurent Fignon had fallen ill with a fever and did not start the stage.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Shortly after the start of the stage, Dominique Arnaud (Reynolds) attacked.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] When he began the ascent of the Tourmalet, he held a lead of 13 minutes over the field.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] A select group of favourites crossed the summit, led by Millar, now just over 7 minutes behind Arnaud.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] As they began the descent, Hinault attacked again, opening a gap to his opponents.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] As he reached the valley, his lead was at 43 seconds.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] At the summit of the Aspin, Hinault's lead had increased to two minutes and he caught up with Arnaud on the subsequent descent.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] However, unlike the day before, the other favourites worked together to give chase, with Millar, Herrera, and Urs Zimmermann (Carrera Jeans–Vagabond) committed to bringing Hinault back as the group reached the climb of the Peyresourde.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] They made contact with him on the descent and as the group began the final climb to Superbagnères, it became clear that Hinault had overexerted himself, falling back quickly.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Hampsten, who had caught up with the LeMond group, attacked during the early part of the climb to soften up the opposition for LeMond.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] While Herrera suffering from cramp dropped back to his team car, LeMond counter-attacked, leaving Zimmermann and Millar behind and joined his teammate at the head of the race.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] With Hampsten falling behind soon after, LeMond continued to the finish alone and won the stage.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Hinault trailed in eleventh, 4:39 minutes behind LeMond.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] He therefore maintained the lead of the race overall, but now just 40 seconds ahead of second-placed LeMond.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Incidentally, LeMond had gained back the exact amount of time he had lost the previous day.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] At the team hotel later in the evening, La Vie Claire owner Bernard Tapie had to intervene in an argument between his two leaders and Andrew Hampsten described the mood on the squad from then on as "super tense".
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The fourteenth stage led the race to Blagnac and was won by Niki Rüttimann (La Vie Claire).
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The team had placed riders in every escape group of the day, and after about 100 km (62 mi), Rüttimann managed to stay away with three other riders.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] They exchanged attacks in the final 5 km (3.1 mi) of the stage, with Rüttimann putting in the decisive move to win solo ahead of his pursuers, jumping into eighth place in the general classification.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] LeMond managed to gain six bonus seconds at an intermediate sprint, closing the gap on Hinault in the general classification to 34 seconds.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Frank Hoste (Fagor) won stage 15 in a two-man sprint against Silvano Contini (Gis Gelati).
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The main field came in just eight seconds behind, but Luis Herrera lost 49 seconds after failing to bridge a gap in the peloton.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The final day before the Alps was stage 16, ending in the town of Gap.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The peloton had to endure significant crosswinds during the stage, accompanied by several attacks from the field.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] After 120 km (75 mi), Hinault was part of a group of four riders splitting away from the field in the winds, quickly making contact with another four-man break to form an escape of eight riders.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] While Hinault was joined by teammates Rüttimann and Winterberg, the group also contained Zimmermann, third overall.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] LeMond, crucially, had missed the move, but his three teammates in the breakaway still rode hard tempo, drawing out an advantage of 52 seconds.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] LeMond, again bound not to chase his own teammates, asked Robert Millar for help, who agreed to have his Panasonic–Merckx–Agu team do the chase work, while LeMond promised to gift Millar a stage should they finish close together.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] After 28 km (17 mi), the groups were back together.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Jean-François Bernard from La Vie Claire won the stage after the two other riders in the final breakaway both punctured a tyre on the descent of the Col d'Espreaux.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] He moved up into thirteenth place in the general classification, which meant that La Vie Claire now had five riders in the top thirteen places.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Because of Hinault's breakaway tactics during the stage, Lemond threatened to resign from the race and had to be calmed by Tapie.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] According to Hampsten, the team was split into three groups: the French riders around Hinault, the two Swiss riders in between, and the other riders on LeMond's side.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Jean-François Bernard supported this view, saying: "The division was real.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Even if it wasn't evident day-to-day, or on the surface, it was there the whole Tour.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] You could feel it." Hinault was unapologetic, saying: "What's his [LeMond's] problem?
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Stage 17 finished on the Col du Granon, the highest mountain-top finish in Tour history up to that point, at an elevation of 2,413 m (7,917 ft).
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Before the Col du Granon, the riders also had to ride across the Col de Vars and the Col d'Izoard.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Eduardo Chozas (Teka) was in a 150 km (93 mi) solo breakaway and won the stage.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Behind him, Hinault began to struggle on the climb of the Izoard, falling behind the other contenders.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] He suffered from pain in his left knee, a recurrence of an injury sustained in 1983.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] LeMond attacked as the group began the descent from the Col d'Izoard and was joined by Zimmermann.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Zimmermann set a strong pace on the final climb to the Col du Granon and took second place on the stage, 6:26 minutes behind Chozas, with LeMond right behind him.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Hinault came in thirteenth, losing 3:21 minutes to LeMond, who took over the race lead.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] LeMond led Zimmermann by 2:24 minutes, with Hinault a further 23 seconds behind.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] It was the first time that a rider from the USA wore the yellow jersey in the history of the Tour.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The night before stage 18 to Alpe d'Huez, Hinault called a team meeting, complaining about the fact that Zimmermann now split the two La Vie Claire riders.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] He called for the team to attack Zimmermann the following day, "until he was broken".
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Another dispute broke out with LeMond, who pointed out that with a time trial still to come, a discipline that did not favour Zimmermann, there was no need for an all-out attack.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Tapie had to talk to the riders until four o'clock in the morning to handle the situation.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Shortly after the start of the stage in Briançon, the first climb of the day was the Col du Lautaret.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] A breakaway formed, including Herrera and Winterberg, who left their companions on the following climb, the Col du Galibier.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Behind them, in the group of favourites, Zimmermann was closely guarding LeMond, while Hinault made several small accelerations to test the opposition.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] On the descent of the Galibier, Hinault attacked, only 150 km (93 mi) into the stage.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] He caught Herrera and Winterberg and they were joined by LeMond, Bauer and Ruiz Cabestany.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] As they reached the next small climb, the Col du Télégraphe, Hinault attacked again, going clear on his own.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] LeMond, having strict instructions from his team not to work with Zimmermann, was again stuck behind.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] LeMond dropped back to his team car for instructions by coach Paul Köchli, who urged him to attack Zimmermann instead of leading him towards Hinault, who at that point had a lead of about one-and-a-half minutes.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] LeMond attacked shortly before the summit and opened up a gap to Zimmermann on the descent, eventually catching up to Hinault, together with Bauer and Ruiz Cabestany.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Bauer then did the lead work until the foot of the next climb, the Col de la Croix de Fer, where he dropped back.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] On the ascent, Hinault asked LeMond to ease the tempo, due to his aching knee, and set the pace himself.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] By the summit, they led Zimmermann by 2:50 minutes.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] On the descent, both set a high tempo, extending the lead over Zimmermann to 4:30 minutes as they reached the climb of Alpe d'Huez.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Sensing that the French public, clearly favouring Hinault, made LeMond nervous, the former led all the way up the climb, with both riders steadily increasing their advantage over everybody else.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Close to the finish line, LeMond drove alongside Hinault, putting his arm around him for a short conversation.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] At the finish, Hinault took LeMond's hand in an apparent gesture of comradery and they crossed the line together, with Hinault taking the stage win.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Tapie later revealed that he had orchestrated the moment, having told LeMond before the climb to Alpe d'Huez that he had effectively won the race and that he should let Hinault take the stage.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Zimmermann finished third, 5:15 behind the pair.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The illusion of a *détente* between the two La Vie Claire leaders lasted only a few hours.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] In the evening, both appeared on French television in a joint interview with Jacques Chancel.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Asked if the battle between them was over, Hinault answered that it would not be until the final time trial in Saint-Étienne.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] He reiterated the statement on the following day, the only rest day of the Tour.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] During a press conference, he declared: "I'm very proud of what we did together, but let me say one more time: the Tour isn't over.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Go on, ask Greg." LeMond felt betrayed by Hinault's apparent unwillingness to honour the deal between the two riders.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Hinault in turn promised that, should LeMond still lead the Tour after the final time trial, he would not attack again.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] This pledge came at the insistence of Tapie, after LeMond had once again threatened to leave the race should Hinault continue attacking.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Pedro Delgado, winner of stage 12 and lying fifth overall, retired from the race during stage 18, having learned of the death of his mother.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Robert Millar, having been fourth at the summit of the Galibier, lost over 19 minutes during the later part of the stage, dropping from fourth to eighth overall.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] As the conclusion of the race drew closer, LeMond suspected that the public and a large part of the riders would prefer a record-breaking victory for Hinault.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Before the start of stage 19, a journalist suggested to him that 80 per cent of the riders would support Hinault, to which he jokingly replied that he was surprised if twenty per cent supported him.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Indeed, Hinault attacked once more during the stage, during the feed zone, a clear breach of cycling etiquette which dictates that no rider should attack while his competitors take on food and drinks.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Bauer and Hampsten assisted LeMond in bringing Hinault back into the field.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] During an intermediate sprint, Hinault gained back two seconds to cut his disadvantage to 2:43 minutes.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Julián Gorospe won the stage for Reynolds, ahead of Anderson.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Under growing suspicion that other riders would interfere with his race to favour Hinault, LeMond stated after the stage: "If they want to crash me, I'd rather they tell me now.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] I'd rather give the race to them." Hinault's tactics were confusing to other riders as well.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Speaking of the stage, Hampsten later recalled: "It's the only time I ever chased a teammate in my life.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] It felt weird; I felt sick doing it. [...] I knew it was the right thing to do." Phil Anderson, riding for Panasonic–Merckx–Agu, was equally angry with Hinault, scolding him publicly after the stage for attacking his teammate in the yellow jersey.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The night before the time trial, Tour director Jacques Goddet came to see LeMond at dinner and warned him to watch his water bottles and other equipment, saying: "There are many who do not want you to win." LeMond heeded this advice, with his parents buying his own food.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] At the daily doping controls, he left his fingerprint in the sealing wax and photographed the urine bottles.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] According to LeMond, one rider even offered Hinault to cause a crash for LeMond, but Hinault refused.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The decisive stage of the race was the following day, a 58 km (36 mi) time trial around Saint-Étienne.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] After 20 km (12 mi), LeMond was eight seconds faster than Hinault.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] However, with 37 km (23 mi) raced, LeMond crashed in a right-hand corner.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] While he was able to get up quickly and resume, his brake rubbed on the front wheel, making it necessary to change bikes.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Hinault profited from LeMond's mishap to win the stage, but managed to only claw back 25 seconds to his teammate, who finished second.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Both were in a class of their own, with Hinault catching up with Zimmermann at the finish line, even though the latter had started three minutes ahead of him.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Following the stage, Hinault acknowledged his defeat, stating: "After today, we won't fight any more." LeMond now led Hinault by 2:18 minutes.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Stage 21 was the last to feature significant climbing, finishing at the Puy de Dôme.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Hinault, now no longer trying to dislodge LeMond, instead focused on securing his lead in the mountains classification, which he did by collecting maximum points at the top of the Croix de l'Homme, the first climb of the day.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Erich Maechler (Carrera Jeans–Vagabond) won the stage, having moved clear of a leading group at the start of the final ascent.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Second was Ludo Peeters (Kwantum–Decosol–Yoko), 34 seconds behind.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] LeMond came in 6:06 minutes behind, in eighteenth place.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Hinault, having worked for his teammate during the stage, fell back on the final climb and lost 43 seconds to LeMond, who extended his overall advantage to 3:10 minutes.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Robert Millar, fighting sickness, dropped out during this stage.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Guido Bontempi won the final two stages of the race, first stage 22 into Nevers, edging out Hoste and Vanderaerden in a sprint finish.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] On the final, ceremonial stage into Paris, LeMond crashed and Hinault made a point to personally escort him back into the field.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Hinault then contested the final sprint, won by Bontempi, and finished fourth to close out his Tour de France career.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] LeMond became the first rider from an English-speaking country to win the event, at an average speed of 36.92 km/h (22.94 mph).
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Only 132 of the 210 starters finished the race in Paris.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Robert Millar described the race as "by far the hardest" Tour he had ridden, adding: "I don't think we ever climbed the mountains so fast." La Vie Claire was the only team to arrive in Paris with all ten starters.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The *lanterne rouge*, the last-placed finisher of the race, was Ennio Salvador (Gis Gelati), 2:55:51 hours behind LeMond.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] about Hinault and the 1986 Tour de France.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Perception of the 1986 Tour de France and the rivalry between LeMond and Hinault remain divided.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] LeMond felt betrayed by Hinault's failure to live up to the clear assertion that he would assist him to win the Tour, saying: "He made promises to me he never intended to keep.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] He made them just to relieve the pressure on himself." He showed disappointment when the public alleged that he had only won due to Hinault allowing it.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Hinault's view of the 1986 Tour differs from LeMond's.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] After the final time trial, Hinault claimed to have attacked repeatedly to toughen LeMond up, adding: "Next year maybe he'll have to fight off another opponent who will make life miserable for him.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Now he'll know how to fight back." Cycling historians Bill and Carol McGann refuse this argument, writing: "Of course, Hinault reneged on his promise.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] In France, Hinault's aggressive riding style was widely celebrated and did much to improve his public image, which had suffered due to an alleged lack of panache during his Tour wins and his behaviour towards fans and officials.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Robert Millar suggested that he specifically rode the way he did in 1986 to win over the French public.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Friction between LeMond and Hinault continued into the Coors Classic later in the year, the last stage race of Hinault's career.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] When LeMond attacked during a stage to move up from third to second place overall, Hinault accused him of riding against him, who was in the lead.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Hinault, as he had announced previously, retired at the end of the season, on his 32nd birthday.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] LeMond meanwhile was unable to defend his Tour title, suffering a near-fatal hunting accident on Easter 1987.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] He returned to the Tour in 1989, winning the event for a second time and adding a third victory in 1990.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The rivalry between Hinault and LeMond in both the 1985 and 1986 Tours was the subject of the documentary *Slaying the Badger*, part of ESPN's series *30 for 30*.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Based on the book by the same name by journalist Richard Moore, it premiered on 22 July 2014.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] There were several classifications in the 1986 Tour de France, six of them awarding jerseys to their leaders.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The most important was the general classification, calculated by adding each cyclist's finishing times on each stage.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The cyclist with the least accumulated time was the race leader, identified by the yellow jersey; the winner of this classification is considered the winner of the Tour.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] No time bonuses were given at stage finishes, a change from the 1985 edition.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Time bonuses were given for the intermediate sprints.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Over the first half of the race, each intermediate sprint gave 12, 8, and 4 bonus seconds to the first three riders across the line, while during the second half, 6, 4, and 2 seconds were awarded.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] There were 94 intermediate sprints over the course of the 1986 Tour, a record number.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] In the team time trial on stage 2, the real time of the finishing teams was used to calculate the overall classification, taken on the sixth rider of each team to cross the finish line.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The time that could be lost was limited at five minutes, however, if a rider did not finish with the rest of his team, his real time was used, even if it exceeded five minutes.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Additionally, there was a points classification, where cyclists were given points for finishing in the top 25 on a stage.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] All stages awarded the same number of points: 25 for the winner, with each subsequent place receiving one fewer point.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] In this edition, no points were awarded at intermediate sprints.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The cyclist with the most points led the classification, and was identified with a green jersey.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Eric Vanderaerden was the winner of this classification.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] There was also a mountains classification.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The Tour organisers categorised some climbs as either *hors catégorie*, first, second, third, or fourth-category; points for this classification were won by the first cyclists that reached the top of these climbs first, with more points available for the higher-categorised climbs.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Climbs rated *hors catégorie* gave 40 points to the first rider across, down to one point for the 15th rider to reach the summit.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] First-category climbs awarded 30 points, second category ones 20 for the first rider.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Third- and fourth-category mountains awarded 7 and 4 points respectively to the first man across.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The cyclist with the most points led the classification, and wore a white jersey with red polka dots.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Bernard Hinault won the mountains prize.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] There was also a combination classification.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] This classification was calculated as a combination of the other classifications; its leader wore the combination jersey.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Being in first place in the general, points, mountains, or intermediate sprints classification awarded 25 points, down to one point for 25th place.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] For the second consecutive year, Greg LeMond was the winner of this classification.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Another classification was the debutant classification.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] This was decided the same way as the general classification, but only riders that rode the Tour for the first time were eligible, and the leader wore a white jersey.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] 79 out of the 210 starters were eligible.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Andrew Hampsten was the first-placed rider in this classification.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The sixth individual classification was the intermediate sprints classification.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] This classification had similar rules as the points classification, but points were only awarded on intermediate sprints.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Gerrit Solleveld (Kwantum–Decosol–Yoko) won this classification.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] For the team classification, the times of the best three cyclists per team on each stage were added; the leading team was the team with the lowest total time.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The riders in the team that led this classification were identified by yellow caps.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] There was also a team points classification.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Cyclists received points according to their finishing position on each stage, with the first rider receiving one point.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The first three finishers of each team had their points combined, and the team with the fewest points led the classification.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The riders of the team leading this classification wore green caps.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] La Vie Claire won the team classification, while Panasonic–Merckx–Agu won the team points classification.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] In addition, there was a combativity award, in which a jury composed of journalists gave points after each mass-start stage to the cyclist they considered most combative.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] At the conclusion of the Tour, Bernard Hinault won the overall super-combativity award, also decided by journalists.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] The Souvenir Henri Desgrange was given in honour of Tour founder Henri Desgrange to the first rider to pass the summit of the Col du Galibier on stage 18.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Other minor prizes given included one for the best teammate, won by Bruno Leali (Carrera Jeans–Vagabond).
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] An award for the "most amiable" rider was given to Ruiz Cabestany.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Zoetemelk received a prize for fairplay.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] There was also a fairplay award given after every stage, and the winners were allowed to wear special socks during the next stage, showing the logo of Paris' eventually unsuccessful bid to host the 1992 Summer Olympics.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] Between 1977 and 1985, a system of "flying stages" had been used.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] This included a finish line at the middle part of the stage, with the first rider across awarded the same bonuses and prizes as regular stage winners.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p01] However, due to a lack of public acceptance for the concept, it was scrapped for the 1986 edition.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p02] Riders in the Tour competed individually for points that contributed towards the Super Prestige Pernod ranking, an international season-long road cycling competition, with the winner seen as the best all-round rider.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p02] The 250 points accrued by Greg LeMond moved him from fourth to the top of the ranking, replacing Sean Kelly, who did not ride the Tour.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p02] No rider tested positive for performance-enhancing drugs during the 1986 Tour.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p02] Had a positive test occurred, the penalty would have been a ten-minute time penalty for the general classification and a demotion to last place on the stage.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p02] In his book *Rough Ride*, rider Paul Kimmage (RMO–Cycles Méral–Mavic) revealed that during the final stage into Paris, he witnessed riders injecting substances with needles, telling him that they were not afraid to get caught, since only the stage winner and top finishers were tested.
[src:cherbourg/1986-tour-de-france-p02] In a television interview in late 1999, Peter Winnen (Panasonic–Merckx–Agu) revealed that he had used testosterone to help him get through the Tour in 1986.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] The **1994 Tour de France** was the 81st edition of the Tour de France, one of cycling's Grand Tours.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] The Tour began on 2 July with a 7.2 km (4.5 mi) prologue around the French city Lille.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] After 21 more days of racing, the Tour came to a close on the street of the Champs-Élysées.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Twenty-one teams entered the race that was won by Miguel Induráin of the Banesto team.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Second and third respectively were the Latvian Piotr Ugrumov and the Italian rider, Marco Pantani.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Miguel Induráin first captured the lead after the stage 9 individual time trial.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Chris Boardman was the first rider to wear the yellow jersey as leader of the general classification after winning the opening prologue.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Boardman lost the lead to Johan Museeuw after Museeuw's GB–MG Maglificio team won the stage three team time trial.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Flavio Vanzella took the lead away from Museeuw the next day as the Tour made its way into Great Britain.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Vanzella lost the lead to Sean Yates after the race's sixth stage.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Yates led the race for a single day before losing it to Museeuw after the conclusion of stage 7.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Museeuw lost the lead to Indurain after the stage 9 individual time trial, who then successfully defended the lead through the Alps and Pyrenees and to the Tour's finish in Paris.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Indurain became the third rider to win four consecutive Tours de France.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Festina–Lotus won the team classification, which ranked each of the twenty teams contesting the race by lowest cumulative time.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] A total of 21 teams were invited to participate in the 1994 Tour de France.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Fifteen teams were announced in May, based on their UCI ranking: Although the organisation had planned to give five additional wildcards in June, after the 1994 Giro d'Italia, it was decided to invite one extra team, and six wildcards were given.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] The Jolly Componibili–Cage team of Zenon Jaskuła, who had finished in third place in the 1993 Tour de France, was not selected.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Each team sent a squad of nine riders, so the Tour began with a peloton of 189 cyclists; of these, a total of 117 riders made it to the finish in Paris.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] The 1994 edition of the Tour de France began with a short 7.2 km (4.5 mi) prologue that navigated around the French city of Lille.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] There were a total of six stages that held many high mountains, while there was only one hilly stage that contained climbs of lesser degree.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Eleven of the stages were primarily flat stages.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] The official route contained four time trials, three of which were individual and one of which was a team event.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] The tour visited England for the second time to mark the opening of the Channel Tunnel.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Stage 4 began in the Channel port of Dover, running through the Kent and Sussex countryside to Brighton, and Stage 5 was a loop around the naval city of Portsmouth.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Of the stages that contained mountains, four contained summit finishes: stage 11 to Hautacam, stage 12 to Luz Ardiden, stage 16 to Alpe d'Huez, and stage 17 to Val Thorens.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] The nineteenth stage, an individual time trial, had a summit finish to Avoriaz.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] The highest point of elevation in the race was 2,275 m (7,464 ft) at the summit of the Val Thorens climb on stage 17.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] The 1994 edition of the Tour de France began with a brief 7.2 km (4.5 mi) prologue around the city of Lille.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Englishman Chris Boardman set a blistering pace on the course en route to winning the stage by fifteen seconds over the second-place finisher Miguel Induráin.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Stage 1 was a relatively flat stage that came down to a bunch sprint that was marred by a large crash.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] As the riders were sprinting to the finish line, a policeman leaned out to take a photograph causing Wilfried Nelissen to slam on his brakes and crash into the policeman while also taking out Laurent Jalabert in the process.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Djamolidine Abdoujaparov ultimately won the stage while Jalabert and Nelissen were forced to drop out of the race due to the injuries they had sustained.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Amazingly a young Lance Armstrong was able to hold onto a top 10 placing through Stage 10, but other than Rominger no one was in a position to threaten Indurain's lead.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] As the race entered the Pyrenees in stages 11 and 12 Indurain built on his lead over Rominger who abandoned the Tour in Stage 13.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] As the race climbed Mont Ventoux and crossed the Alps Marco Pantani and Piotr Ugrumov began to climb through the top 10 as Richard Virenque held onto 2nd place, but Indurain's lead was secure with Virenque more than 7:00 behind.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] There were several classifications in the 1994 Tour de France.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Additionally, there was a points classification, which awarded a green jersey.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] In the points classification, cyclists got points for finishing among the best in a stage finish, or in intermediate sprints.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] The cyclist with the most points lead the classification, and was identified with a green jersey.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] The organisation had categorised some climbs as either *hors catégorie*, first, second, third, or fourth-category; points for this classification were won by the first cyclists that reached the top of these climbs first, with more points available for the higher-categorised climbs.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] The cyclist with the most points lead the classification, and wore a white jersey with red polka dots.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] The fourth individual classification was the young rider classification, which was not marked by a jersey.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] This was decided the same way as the general classification, but only riders under 26 years were eligible.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] In addition, there was a combativity award given after each mass-start stage to the cyclist considered most combative.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] The decision was made by a jury composed of journalists who gave points.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] The cyclist with the most points from votes in all stages led the combativity classification.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] Eros Poli won this classification, and was given overall the super-combativity award.
[src:cherbourg/1994-tour-de-france] The Souvenir Henri Desgrange was given in honour of Tour founder Henri Desgrange to the first rider to pass the summit of the Col du Tourmalet on stage 12.
[src:cherbourg/1998-french-cantonal-elections] The cantonales elections use the same system as the regional or legislative elections.
[src:cherbourg/1998-french-cantonal-elections] There is a 10% threshold (10% of *registered* voters) needed to proceed to the second round.
[src:cherbourg/1998-french-regional-elections] Regional elections were held in France on 15 March 1998.
[src:cherbourg/1998-french-regional-elections] At stake were the presidencies of each of France's 26 *regions*, which, though they don't have legislative autonomy, manage sizeable budgets.
[src:cherbourg/1998-french-regional-elections] The parliamentary right, led by the conservative Gaullist Rally for the Republic and the centre-right Union for French Democracy won the presidency of 15 of the 26 regions, the rest were won by the French Socialist Party and its allies (Communists, Greens, Radicals).
[src:cherbourg/1998-french-regional-elections] The far-right National Front obtained good results, increasing its number of seats.
[src:cherbourg/1998-french-regional-elections] The far-left and Hunting, Fishing, Nature, Tradition also won seats on various regional councils.
[src:cherbourg/1998-french-regional-elections] These election were the last ones conducted using the D'Hondt method and a closed list proportional representation, with a threshold of five percent of valid votes being applied regionally, later replaced by a two-round mixed-member majoritarian system for the 2004 elections.
[src:cherbourg/1999-european-parliament-election-in-france] European Parliament elections were held in France on 13 June 1999.
[src:cherbourg/1999-european-parliament-election-in-france] Once again, abstention was very high for this type of election- only 47% of eligible voters voted.
[src:cherbourg/1999-european-parliament-election-in-france] The election was also the first French European election to be won by the Socialist Party (PS).
[src:cherbourg/1999-european-parliament-election-in-france] The election ended Sarkozy's immediate political future, including a run for the presidency of the Rally for the Republic – Michèle Alliot-Marie, a close supporter of Chirac, succeeded him.
[src:cherbourg/1999-european-parliament-election-in-france] However, the alliance between Pasqua and de Villiers proved to be ephemeral. de Villiers broke with Pasqua later 2000 and thus ended the RPF's chance to become a large common party for all eurosceptic Gaullists from within the RPR.
[src:cherbourg/1999-european-parliament-election-in-france] The New Union for French Democracy (*Nouvelle UDF*), led by François Bayrou ran independently of the RPR, contrary to Chirac's wishes, for the first time since 1984.
[src:cherbourg/1999-european-parliament-election-in-france] Bayrou won a relatively good result, 9.28%, allowing him to pursue his more independent political strategy (slowly distancing the party from the RPR) within the New UDF.
[src:cherbourg/1999-european-parliament-election-in-france] The other winner of the election were The Greens led by Franco-German green politician Daniel Cohn-Bendit, whose list won 9.72%, the party's second-best result after 1989.
[src:cherbourg/1999-european-parliament-election-in-france] Minor parties, including the agrarian populist Hunting, Fishing, Nature, Traditions and the far-left Workers' Struggle obtained very good results and elected 6 and 5 MEP's respectively.
[src:cherbourg/1999-european-parliament-election-in-france] The far-right FN was penalized by Bruno Megret's dissident MNR list and obtained a low result.
[src:cherbourg/1999-european-parliament-election-in-france] The French Communist Party also did poorly.
[src:cherbourg/1st-marine-artillery-regiment] The **1st Marine Artillery Regiment** (French: *1er Régiment d'Artillerie de Marine, 1er RAMa*) is one of the oldest marine artillery units in the military of France, as part of the troupes de marine within the French Army.
[src:cherbourg/1st-marine-artillery-regiment] The régiment whose origins date back to the seventeenth century, was formally disbanded at Châlons-en-Champagne on 30 June 2015, ending nearly four centuries of service.
[src:cherbourg/1st-marine-artillery-regiment] With two infantry marine regiments it formed the 2nd Brigade of the Blue Division during the Franco-Prussian War.
[src:cherbourg/1st-marine-artillery-regiment] Based in Laon since 1993, it is the artillery regiment of the 2nd Armoured Division.
[src:cherbourg/1st-marine-artillery-regiment] 1956 −1962: A detachment of the regiment participated in operations in Algeria.
[src:cherbourg/1st-marine-artillery-regiment] 1977: The regiment left Melun for the new garrison at Montlhéry.
[src:cherbourg/1st-marine-artillery-regiment] 1993: On 2 August the regiment took its new headquarters in Laon Couvron, a former air base.
[src:cherbourg/1st-marine-artillery-regiment] 1993 - 1996: The 1er RAMa sends detachments in Bosnia and Herzegovina, in the Rapid Reaction Force (RRF) (Serb bombardment of the batteries Mount Igman) during the bombing of Bosnia Herzegovina by NATO 1995ou of IFOR, in charge of enforcing the Dayton.
[src:cherbourg/1st-marine-artillery-regiment] 2009: The regiment received the first cannon CAESAR June 10 This gun replaces the AMX AUF1 in service since 1990.
[src:cherbourg/1st-marine-artillery-regiment] On 1 August it left the 2nd Armoured Brigade, after 42 years and joined the 1st Mechanised Brigade.
[src:cherbourg/1st-marine-artillery-regiment] 2015: The regiment was formally disbanded at Châlons-en-Champagne, after nearly four centuries of service, on 30 June 2015.
[src:cherbourg/1st-marine-artillery-regiment] The banner is decorated with the Cross of the Legion of Honor, the Croix de Guerre 1914-1918 (two palms), the Croix de Guerre 1939-1945 (three palms) and the Cross of Liberation.
[src:cherbourg/1st-marine-artillery-regiment] He is entitled to use the forage in the colors of ribbon the Croix de Guerre 1914 1918 since August 13, 1918, with olive-colored ribbon for the Croix de Guerre 1939-1945.
[src:cherbourg/1st-marine-artillery-regiment] Then from 18 June 1996 to feed the ribbon colors of the Croix de la Liberation.
[src:cherbourg/2001-french-cantonal-elections] Cantonal elections to elect half the membership of the general councils of France's 100 departments were held on 11 and 18 March 2001.
[src:cherbourg/2001-french-cantonal-elections] While the left did poorly in the municipal elections held on the same dates, it emerged as the overall winner in the cantonal elections, gaining control of six departments and losing that of just one.
[src:cherbourg/2001-french-cantonal-elections] The cantonal elections use a two-round system similar to that employed in the country's legislative elections.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Cherbourg is protected by Cherbourg Harbour, between La Hague and Val de Saire, and the city has been a strategic position over the centuries, disputed between the English and French.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Cited as one of the "keys to the kingdom" by Vauban, it became, by colossal maritime development work, a first-rate military port under the leadership of Napoleon I, and holds an arsenal of the French Navy.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] A stopping point for prestigious transatlantic liners in the first half of the 20th century, Cherbourg was the primary goal of US troops during the invasion of Normandy in 1944.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Along with its use as a military, fishing and yachting port, it is also a cross-Channel ferry port, with routes to the English ports of Poole and Portsmouth, and to Dublin and Rosslare Harbour in Ireland.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Limited by its geographical isolation from being a great commercial port, it is nonetheless an important shipbuilding centre, and a working-class city with a rural hinterland.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Cherbourg is located at the northern tip of the Cotentin Peninsula, in the department of Manche, of which it is a subprefecture.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] At the time of the 1999 census the city of Cherbourg had an area of 6.91 square kilometres (2.668 sq mi), while the city of Octeville had an area of 7.35 km2 (2.838 sq mi).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The largest city in the Department of Manche, it is the result of the merger of the communes of Cherbourg and Octeville.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The amalgamated city today has an area of 14.26 km2 (5.506 sq mi).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Cherbourg is situated at the mouth of the Divette and at the south of the bay between Cap Lévi to the east and Cap de La Hague to the west, Cherbourg-Octeville is 120 km (75 mi) from the English coast.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Cherbourg and Octeville-sur-Cherbourg once belonged to the deanery of La Hague, delimited by the Divette.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] In 1786, a part of Equeurdreville joined Cherbourg, during the construction of the port, and then in 1802, a portion of Octeville.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Since 1811, the "mielles" [dunes] of Tourlaville, commune of the deanery of Saire, are integrated into the Cherbourg territory known as the quarter of Val-de-Saire where the Pasteur Hospital and the Saint-Clement Church were built.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Thus, Cherbourg-Octeville lies both in La Hague and in the Val de Saire.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Like all Chantereyne and the area of the Mielles, the Cherbourg territory was reclaimed from the sea.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Built at the level of the sea, the town developed at the foot of the Roule mountain (highest point of the old town) and la Fauconnière.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Octeville is a former rural municipality, composed of hamlets, whose settlement extended from the 19th century and whose territory is highly urbanised since 1950, especially around the ZUP of the provinces and the university campus.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The bordering communes are Tourlaville to the east, Équeurdreville-Hainneville to the west, La Glacerie to the south and southeast, Martinvast to the south, and Nouainville and Sideville to the south-west.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Located at the end of the Armorican Massif, Cherbourg retains traces of the geologic formation, deformed granites and metamorphic schists of the Precambrian of Hercynian orogeny by the folding of the arkoses of the Cambrian and Armorican sandstone and shale of the Ordovician.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] These folds result in layers of sandstone tilted 45° towards the north-east on la Fauconniere (including "La Roche qui pend" ['the hanging rock']) and the Montagne du Roule.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] These two cliffs are due to sea erosion in the Quaternary.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The retreat of the sea then gave way to sand dunes and tidal marshes, destroyed by the urbanisation of the 17th and 19th centuries, identical to those of Collignon in Tourlaville.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] These rocks in the soil have been used for centuries in several ways: Crushed granite extracted in Querqueville and arkoses of Becquet, have been used for the manufacture of rubble (moellon) and blocks squared for lintels.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The greenschist, whose colour comes from chlorite and sericite, are used mainly for roofing in Nord-Cotentin, but also masonry in Cherbourg.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The Armorican sandstone of the Montagne du Roule is used for rubble and rockfill.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Most of the many quarries, which opened in the metropolitan area for building the harbour wall, are now closed.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The streams of the Bucaille and the Fay, which watered the *Croûte du Homet*, disappeared in the 18th century during the construction of the military port.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Cherbourg has a temperate oceanic climate.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Its maritime character causes high humidity (84%) and a strong sea wind, commonly stormy but also low seasonal variations of temperature and few days of frost (7.3).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The combined effect of the wind and the tides can generate a rapid change of weather in a single day, with sun and rain which can be a few hours apart.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The influence of the Gulf Stream and the mildness of the winter allow the naturalisation of many Mediterranean and exotic plants (mimosas, palms, agaves, etc.) which are present in the public and private gardens of the city, despite average insolation.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The climate is similar to areas much further north in Great Britain and Ireland due to the moderation.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Summers are far cooler than expected by French standards.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Historically, Cherbourg is at the western end of Route nationale 13, which runs through the city by the "Rouges Terres" and the *Avenue de Paris*, from La Glacerie.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] An extension to Cherbourg is in the works, with the doubling of the bridge over the *Port des Flamands*, to ensure a continuity of the dual carriageway to the commercial port in Cherbourg.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The old Route nationale 801 (reclassified as D901), which connects Cap de la Hague to Barfleur, crosses the city from east to west.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] After the completion of the bypass east of the agglomeration, a western bypass project is under study, and a 'zone' corresponding to the future final route has been selected.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Similarly, upgrading to a dual carriageway for access of Maupertus Airport is envisaged.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The D650 is used to connect Cherbourg to the west coast of the Cotentin peninsula.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Departing from Cherbourg, the D650 takes a southwesterly direction to Les Pieux and then along to join the *Côte des Isles* (the Channel Islands coast) to Barneville-Carteret.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] In the approach to Cherbourg, this road has undergone development, in recent years, with amenities (roundabouts, traffic lights, urban development) by virtue of the peri-urbanisation of the communes in its path.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] With the awarding of autoroute status to the RN13 in 2006, the work of upgrading to motorway standard between Cherbourg and Caen is being undertaken over a 10-year period.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The construction work of the RN13 at the entrance of the Cherbourg agglomeration (locality *Virage des Chèvres*) was completed in early 2009.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Cherbourg-Octeville is a port on the English Channel with a number of regular passenger and freight ferry services operating from the large modern ferry terminal and has a major artificial harbour.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The port welcomes some 30 cruise ships per year including the largest, thanks to a cruise terminal built in 2006 in the Gare Maritime de Cherbourg, which had opened in 1933 on the *Quai de France* next to the *Cité de la Mer*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Frequently, cruise ships that have planned for another destination have taken refuge in the port, for protection from the frequent storms.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Conventional cargo ships berth in the eastern area of the docks on the *Quai des Flamands* and *Quai des Mielles*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] During the construction of the Concorde prototypes in the 1960s, some sections built in the United Kingdom passed by ferry through Cherbourg, for transfer to Toulouse.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The Paris - Cherbourg railway line, operated by Réseau Ferré de France, ends at Cherbourg railway station, which opened in 1858 and welcomes a million passengers every year.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] This line continued, at the beginning of the 20th century, up to the resort of Urville-Nacqueville and was complemented by the *Tue-Vâques* which served from Cherbourg to Val de Saire between 1911 and 1950.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Today, the Intercités Paris-Caen-Cherbourg line is the most profitable in its class with profit over €10 million per year despite numerous incidents and delays.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Regular services operate to Paris-Saint-Lazare via Caen using Intercités stock, local TER services operate from the station to Lisieux via Caen and to Rennes via Saint-Lô.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Intercités services to Paris-Saint-Lazare take three hours on average.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] From July 2009 to December 2010, a TGV Cherbourg – Dijon service operated, via Mantes and Roissy TGV.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] With one daily round-trip, it operated experimentally for three years and gave the people of Cherbourg direct access by rail to France's primary airport.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The service ceased prematurely, as the minimum threshold of passenger traffic was not met.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] As well as a main line station there was also the *Gare Maritime Transatlantique* station.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] This now forms part of the *Cité de la mer*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The *Compagnie des transports de Cherbourg* (CTC) was created in 1896, connecting the *Place de Tourlaville* and the *Place du Château* by a tramway in Cherbourg, then to Urville.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] After the German occupation and bombardment of the tram depot, the use of buses took over, and it was not until 1962 that the network had several lines.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] From 1976, the *Communauté urbaine de Cherbourg* supported the jurisdiction of public transit.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Management of the public service is delegated to Keolis, the CTC took the name of Zephir Bus in 1991.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The network covers the whole of the metropolitan area.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] In recent years, a night bus service has also been created.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Cherbourg-Octeville and its suburbs are also served by the Manéo departmental bus service.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The Cherbourg – Maupertus Airport, located in Maupertus-sur-Mer, serves the city.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Its 2,440 m (8,010 ft) runway hosts charter flights.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] After stopping the daily service to Paris by Twin Jet, in spring 2008, a new link with Caen and Paris started with Chalair on 27 October 2008.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] With 40,500 passengers in 2007, the airport had lost 30% of its commercial passengers, and 10% of its total traffic over a year.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The origin of the coat of arms is disputed.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] According to Victor Le Sens, it is of religious origin: Fess argent charged of stars represents the belt of the Virgin Mary, one of the two patrons of the city and the number of stars, like the bezants, evokes the Trinity, the other patron of the city.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The bezants would be the expression of the redemption of the captives, illustrating the participation of the notables of Cherbourg on the Third Crusade.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The coat of arms of Cherbourg dates from the late 12th century, at the time of the Crusades.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The sable signifies prudence and constancy in adversity, the azure denotes activity and the seas.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Canel had explained before him that the bezants and stars respectively illustrated trade and sea port.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The stars, absent from the armorial of d'Hozier in 1697, were added in the 18th century.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Under the Empire, the coat of arms was completed by a free area of second-class towns which is to dexter azure to an "N" of or, surmounted by a pointed star of the same, brocading at the ninth of the escutcheon.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Regarding the external ornaments, the mural crown symbolises protection and happiness, the caduceus of trade and business, the olive tree of peace, the oak of strength, recalling the role of both the military and commercial port.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The argent means that Cherbourg was a second class city under the Empire.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Today, the municipality of Cherbourg-Octeville uses a logo, entitled *"mouette musicale"* [musical seagull].
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Initially adopted by Cherbourg, it consists of a gull, symbolising the maritime character of the town, on a musical stave, evoking the musicality of the port: "The cry of the seagulls that dance between sky and sea, the mermaids of ships and the melodious song of the waves".
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The date of Foundation of Cherbourg can not be set precisely, although several local historians, including Robert Lerouvillois, trace the origin of the city to Coriallo (for **Coriovallo*) of the Unelli.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] According to Pierre-Yves Lambert, the Celtic element *corio-* means "army, troop" and the element *vallo-* similar to the Latin *vallum*, would be "rampart, fortification".
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Mentioned on the *Tabula Peutingeriana* (c.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] 365), in the Antonine Itinerary and the *Gesta* de Fontenelle ("In pago Coriovallinse", 747-753), *Coriallo*, Latinised then as *Coriallum*, hosted a Roman garrison during the late Roman Empire, and the recovered remains would be the village between Cherbourg and Tourlaville, on the Mielles.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The Cotentin Peninsula was the first territory conquered by the Vikings in their ninth century invasion.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] After the Anglo-Scandinavian settlement, a new name appeared there in a still Latinised form: *Carusburg Castellum* (1026-1027, Fauroux 58) then *Carisburg* (1056–1066, Fauroux 214), *Chiersburg* (William of Jumièges, v.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] *Carusburg* would mean "fortress of the marsh" in Old Norse *kjarr* (marsh), and *borg* (castle, fortified town) or "city of the marais" in Old English *ker* (bog) and *burgh* (town).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The element *kjarr* / *ker* is also found in Normandy in Villequier and Orcher.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] According to François de Beaurepaire, it comes rather from the Old English *chiriche* (spelled *ċiriċe*, Church) or [tch] is reduced to [s], as the commune of Chirbury, in the County of Shropshire, formerly also spelled *Chirichburig* (915) and *Chiresbir* (1226).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The name of Octeville appears meanwhile, in 1063, in a Charter of William the Conqueror about allocations made to the Collegiate Church of Cherbourg.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] It means: "the rural area of *Otti*", a Scandinavian male name also found in Octeville-l'Avenel, Octeville-sur-Mer and Otby (Lincolnshire, *Ottebi*, 11th century).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Cherbourg is also the name of a Canadian township, located between Matane and Les Méchins, which gave its name to the communes of Saint-Thomas-de-Cherbourg, merged in 1954 into Les Méchins, and Saint-Jean-de-Cherbourg.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] This name, including the proclamation date of 7 May 1864, could be due to the impact by the local newspapers of the inauguration of the military port by Napoleon III in 1858.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Cherbourg is also the name of a town in Queensland, Australia.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The Cotentin, conquered by Quintus Titurius Sabinus in 56 BC, was divided between the *pagus constantiensis* ("County of Coutances") and the *pagus coriovallensis* ("County of Coriallo"), within Gallia Lugdunensis.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Coriallo housed a small garrison and a castrum was built on the left bank of the Divette as an element of the *Litus saxonicum*, after Saxon raids at the beginning of the fourth century.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] In 497, the village was sold with all of Armorica to Clovis.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] It was evangelised by Saint Éreptiole in 432, then by Saint Exuperat, Saint Leonicien, and finally Saint Scubilion in 555.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] In 870, Saint Clair, landing in Kent, was ordained priest of Cherbourg and established a hermitage in the surrounding forest.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] After several Norman raids in the ninth century, Cherbourg was attached to the Duchy of Normandy along with the Cotentin, in 933, by William Longsword.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The Danish King Harold moved there in 946.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] In the face of English threats, Richard III of Normandy strengthened the fortifications of the castle at the same time as those of the other major strongholds of Cotentin.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] In 1053, the city was one of the four main cities of the duchy of William the Conqueror to receive an annuity in perpetuity for the maintenance of one hundred needy.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] In 1139, during the struggle for succession to the Anglo-Norman Crown, Cherbourg fell after two months of siege to the troops of Stephen of England before being retaken in 1142 by Geoffrey of Anjou, whose wife, Empress Matilda, three years later founded the Abbaye Notre-Dame du Vœu.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] During the conquest of Normandy by Philip II of France, Cherbourg fell without a fight in 1204.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The city was sacked in 1284 and 1293, the abbey and the Hôtel-Dieu looted and burned, but the castle, where the population was entrenched, resisted.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Following these ravages, Philip IV of France fortified the city in 1300.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Its strategic position, a key to the kingdom along with Calais as a bridgehead for invasion by the English and French, the town was much disputed during the Hundred Years' War.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Having one of the strongest castles in the world according to Froissart, it changed ownership six times as a result of transactions or seats, never by force of arms.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The fortress resisted the soldiers of Edward III in 1346.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] In February 1354, Cherbourg was transferred by John II of France to Charles II of Navarre with the bulk of the Cotentin.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The city was of Navarre from 1354 to 1378, and Charles II stayed in Cherbourg on several occasions.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] In 1378, the city was besieged by Charles V of France as the rest of the Norman possessions of the King of Navarre, but in vain.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Navarre troops who had dropped the County of Évreux and the Cotentin were entrenched in Cherbourg, already a difficult taking, and defended it against French attacks.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] In June 1378, having lost ground in Normandy, Charles II of Navarre rented Cherbourg in 1378 to Richard II of England for a period of three years.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Bertrand du Guesclin besieged it for six months using many machines of war, but abandoned the siege in December 1378.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The King of England then refused to return the city to the Navarrese, despite the efforts of Charles II.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] It was only his son Charles III of Navarre who recovered it in 1393.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] In 1404, it was returned to Charles VI of France, in exchange for the Duchy of Nemours.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Fallen in 1418 to the hands of the English, Cherbourg, the last English possession of the Duchy of Normandy after the Battle of Formigny, was retaken by France following the Siege of Cherbourg in 1450.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] On 28 April 1532, Cherbourg was visited with great fanfare by Francis I and the dauphin.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] At that time, Cherbourg was described by Gilles de Gouberville as a fortified town of 4,000 residents, protected by drawbridges at the three main gates which were permanently guarded and closed from sunset until dawn.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Inside the city walls, the castle, itself protected by wide moats and equipped with a keep and twelve towers, was south-east of the city.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Outside and to the south of the city walls, the suburb along the Divette was frequented by sailors.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Cherbourg was not affected by the wind of the Reformation that divided Normandy, consolidated and heavily guarded by Matignon, Henry III thanked his defence against the troops of Montgomery, as lieutenant-general of Normandy and Governor of Cherbourg in 1578, and then marshal the following year.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The bourgeois also remained loyal to Henry III and Henry IV, when Normandy was mostly held by the Catholic League.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] To complement the two major ports of Brest on the Atlantic Ocean and Toulon on the Mediterranean Sea, Louis XIV wished to build a new port on the side of the English Channel, facing England, in order to shelter the passing ships.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] In 1686, Vauban offered to strengthen the fortifications of Cherbourg, and close Cherbourg Harbour with two sea walls, but preferred La Hogue for the establishment of a major military port.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Fortifications and the castle development work began the following year but were stopped by the King in December 1688, influenced by Louvois and fear of English attacks.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] In the absence of these fortifications, the population of Cherbourg attended to the destruction of the three ships of Admiral Tourville at the end of the Battle of La Hogue.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The commercial port dug at the current position of the *place Divette* between 1739 and 1742, was devastated in August 1758 by an English attack under the orders of General Bligh and Admiral Howe.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] During the Seven Years' War, the British briefly occupied the town after the Raid on Cherbourg in 1758.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The British destroyed military buildings and warehouses before departing.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The population increased from 800 feus (4,000 inhabitants) in Cherbourg and 95 in Octeville, around 1715, to 7,300 people in Cherbourg by 1778.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Louis XVI decided to relaunch the project of the port on the English Channel.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] After many delays, it was decided in 1779 to build a 4 km (2.5 mi)-long sea wall between île Pelée and the tip of Querqueville, using a method developed by Louis-Alexandre de Cessart, a pier of 90 wooden cones of 20 m (66 ft) by 20, filled with rubble, connected by iron chains.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The first cone was immersed on 6 June 1784, and the King attended the launching of the ninth cone on 22 June.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] But the technique did not withstand storms and was abandoned in 1788 in favour of scuttling old warships to backfill lost stones touted by La Bretonnière.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] However, the reduction of subsidies and the revolutionary events slowed work down, until its suspension in 1792.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] A new Hôtel de Ville (town hall) was completed in 1804.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] First Consul Bonaparte wanted to turn Cherbourg into a major military port, for the invasion of the United Kingdom.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] He charged Joseph Cachin with the resumption of the work of the sea wall, the digging of military outer harbour, and the construction of the new arsenal.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] After a visit in 1811, Napoleon made Cherbourg a maritime prefecture, a *chef-lieu* of the Arrondissements of the Manche department and the seat of a court of first instance.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The work of the central sea wall, interrupted again between 1813 and 1832, ended in 1853, the east and west sea walls in 1895.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The Charles X docks (begun in 1814 - 290 × 220 × 18 metres) and Napoleon III (started in 1836 - 420 × 200 × 18 m) of the military port were respectively opened on 25 August 1829, in the presence of the Dauphin, and 7 August 1858, by the Imperial couple.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The work of the sea wall was concluded by the construction of the small harbour (Homet sea wall, 1899-1914 and sea wall of the Flemings, 1921–1922).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The work of the port led the intensification and spread of a modernising and developing Cherbourg, while contractors, owners, and local merchants were getting richer.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] After the creation of the *Route des Pieux* (current *Rue Salengro* and *Rue Carnot*), the town was formed around an homogenised street-village then urbanising at the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] On 16 August 1830, King Charles X, dethroned, departed into exile from the military port of Cherbourg aboard the *Great Britain*, leaving room for the July Monarchy.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] After seeing moor in its harbour *Le Luxor* carrying the Obelisk of Luxor in August 1833, Cherbourg welcomed the return of the remains of Napoleon to France aboard the *Belle Poule*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] On 4 August 1858, an equestrian statue of Napoleon by the sculptor Armand Le Véel, was erected on the occasion of the visit of Napoleon III to the inauguration of the railway line from Cherbourg to Paris.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Visualizing the fight from a sailboat, Manet immortalised it in *The Battle of the Kearsarge and the Alabama*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] In November 1984, the French Navy mine hunter *Circé* discovered a wreck under nearly 60 m (200 ft) of water off Cherbourg.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Captain Max Guerout later confirmed the wreck to be of the CSS *Alabama*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] From 1847, the geographical and technical properties of the port of Cherbourg attracted shipping companies linking European ports to the east coast of the United States.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] At the end of the 1860s, the ships of the Royal Mail Steam Packet Company and the Hamburg America Line anchored in the harbour before crossing the Atlantic.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] After leaving Southampton, England, the RMS *Titanic* made its first stop at Cherbourg on 10 April 1912, during its maiden voyage, where an additional 274 passengers embarked.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] In 1913, Cherbourg received 500 ships and 70,000 passengers.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] On 31 July 1909, Tsar Nicholas II and French president Armand Fallières met officially in Cherbourg to reinforce the Franco-Russian Alliance.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] During the First World War, traffic was completely suspended.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Cherbourg became the place of arrival for equipment and the British and American troops, and for departure on leave and injuries.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The military port experienced an increase in activity, and the garrison stationed at Cherbourg was reinforced.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The port infrastructures were developed to receive coal and oil required for the conflict.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Traffic doubled, reaching 600,000 tons in 1918.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Transatlantic transit resumed in the aftermath of the war with the British, American and Dutch transatlantic companies.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] To welcome the best stopovers, the Chamber of Commerce built a deep water port, a new ferry terminal, and an area dedicated to loading, unloading and storage of goods in the field of Mielles.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Cherbourg became the first port of migration in Europe, and Cunard Line, White Star Line and Red Star Line companies united to build the *Hôtel Atlantique* [Atlantic Hotel] intended to receive emigrants before crossing.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] At the same time, the downtown was renovated, especially in the architectural projects of René Levesque, Drancey and René Levavasseur.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] However, the 1929 crisis put an end to the transatlantic peak.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] During the Second World War (1939–1945), the German Army occupied the north of France and fortified the coastline against invasion.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] As a deep-water port, Cherbourg was of strategic importance, very heavily protected against seaborne assault.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] German troops arrived in the outskirts of Cherbourg on 17 June 1940, towards the end of the Battle of France.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Four years later, Cherbourg, the only deep-water port in the region, was the primary objective of the American troops who had landed at Utah Beach during the Battle of Normandy.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The Battle of Cherbourg was required to give the Allies a point of logistic support for human resupply and material of the troops.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] American troops encircled the city on 21 June 1944.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] At the end of furious street fighting and bitter resistance from the Fort du Roule, *Generalleutnant* Karl-Wilhelm von Schlieben, *Konteradmiral* Walter Hennecke and 37,000 German soldiers surrendered on 29 June to Major General Joseph Lawton Collins, Commanding General (CG) of the U.S.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] After a month of demining and repairs by American and French engineers, the port, completely razed by the Germans and the bombing, welcomed the first Liberty ships and became, until the victory of 1945, the busiest port in the world, with traffic double that of the Port of New York .
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] It was also the endpoint of the gasoline and diesel which crossed the English Channel via the underwater pipeline PLUTO (Pipe Line Under The Ocean), and the starting point of the Red Ball Express, the truck transport circuit to Chartres.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Cherbourg was returned to France by the Americans on 14 October 1945.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] It was cited in the Order of the Army on 2 June 1948 and received the Croix de guerre with Palm.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The wartime destruction was mainly concentrated around the military port in Cherbourg but had hit 60% of Octeville.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Thanks to the urgency of the port reconstruction, economic activity resumed quickly.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Cherbourg, headed by former SFIO Minister René Schmitt, built much social housing.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The postwar boom led to the modernisation of the economy and a greater role for female employment.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Under the leadership of General de Gaulle, Cherbourg became the hub of nuclear ballistic missile submarine construction from 1964, including the first, *Le Redoutable*, which was launched in 1967.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Félix Amiot's shipyard Constructions Mécaniques de Normandie, specialised in military armaments, became famous during the Christmas of 1969 in an episode of the Cherbourg Project.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Incorporated in 1970, the Communauté urbaine de Cherbourg gathered together Cherbourg and Octeville, La Glacerie, Tourlaville, Querqueville and Équeurdreville-Hainneville.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] From the end of the 1960s, the nuclear industry emerged through the construction sites of the La Hague reprocessing plant and the Flamanville Nuclear Power Plant in addition to submarines of the DCN.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] A union of trade unions, left-wing activists and environmentalists, formed around the fear of the "nuclearisation" of Nord-Cotentin, crystallised in January 1979 when the *Pacific Fisher* landed with the first spent nuclear waste from Japan.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] On the eve of the 1980s, the Cherbourg agglomeration was hit by several violent social conflicts, particularly due to the closure of the Babcock factories.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The major decisions of the public authorities, on which Cherbourg has depended for many centuries, and the nuclear industry, caused a deep economic crisis in the 1990s.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The Arsenal was drastically downsized, the Northern Fleet (FLONOR) moved to Brest in 1992, and the maritime hospital closed.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] UIE, Burty, CMN, Socoval and Alcatel accumulated social plans or closings.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Under the auspices of the urban community, the agglomeration developed its academic offerings with the IUT of Cherbourg-Manche, the School of Engineers of Cherbourg and a branch of the University of Caen, which complemented INTECHMER and the School of Fine Arts.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The new millennium began with the creation of a new commune.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Cherbourg-Octeville was created on 1 March 2000 through the joining of Cherbourg and Octeville, following a local referendum within *"Grand Cherbourg"*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The city revived its tourist and maritime identity through the Cité de la Mer and the opening to the public of the *Redoubtable*, and became the home of stopovers for cruises and nautical events.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The urban renewal operation "between land and sea", with an emphasis on the commercial and touristic attractiveness of the city and the Bassins Quarter, as well as the economic specialisation in boating, emerged.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Meanwhile, the traditional activities of the port (passengers, freight and fishing) were in crisis.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The Norman language writer Alfred Rossel, a native of Cherbourg, composed many songs which form part of the heritage of the region.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Rossel's song "Sus la mér" ("on the sea") is often sung as a regional patriotic song.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The local dialect is known as Cotentinais.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] La Glacerie was named for glass factory.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] In 1655, Louis Lucas de Néhou built a glass factory which produced windows and mirrors for such buildings as the Galerie des Glaces and Château de Versailles.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] The factory in La Glacerie was destroyed by Allied bombardments in 1944 during the Normandy invasion.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p01] Cherbourg was the first site outside the United States to be designated as an American Civil War Heritage Site by the Civil War Preservation Trust because a sea battle was fought nearby in 1864 by Union and Confederate warships.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Cherbourg originally developed on the left bank of the mouth of the Divette, around the castle.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Traces of the ancient fortress are rare in the modern city; the fortification was located in the area bounded by the *Rue de la Marine*, *Quai de Caligny*, the *Foch*, *Gambetta*, *Albert-Mahieu* and *François-Lavieille* streets, and *La République* and *La Trinité* squares.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The city had five streets: *Grande Rue*, *Rue de la Trinité* (today, Tour-Carrée), the *Rue du Nouet* (to the Blé), the *Rue au Fourdray* and *Rue Onfroy* (of trade), and a dozen boëls (alleys).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] These five medieval streets were transformed into pedestrian streets in the 1980s.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Until the destruction of the city walls, the main road called *rue de-devant-le-château*, was built on its west (east is bordered by ditches) with several houses with arcades, called *soliers*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] After the dismantling of the walls, inside which lived three-fifths of the population, the city extended up to its natural boundaries at the end of the 17th century: the Divette in the east, and Chantereine stream in the west.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] During the 19th century, it extended to the neighbouring annexed territories of Tourlaville and Équeurdreville.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Its rapid growth from the end of the 18th century was spoken of by Jean Fleury, in 1839, in that it *"offers almost everywhere the appearance of a new town; the old streets occupy little space, and the others are generally large and airy, the fountains numerous [...].
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Damaged during all eras, rebuilt in piecemeal, the city has no architectural unity.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Shale, extracted from the quarries of the agglomeration, is the traditional material of construction.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] With widespread coverage in the northern Cotentin, it is also used in Cherbourg for the walls in the city, apparent or often covered with a grayish or sometimes colourful coating.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The frames are then Valognes stone (limestone), pink granite of Fermanville, or brick, and the underpinnings Armorican sandstone of the Roule and the Fauconniere.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The expansion of the city from the 18th century contributed to the diversity of materials.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The use of Caen stone and industrial brick was necessary under the Second Empire, while vernacular architecture disappeared gradually in these years in favour of a more homogeneous and Parisian style.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Cherbourg and its agglomeration urbanised around the ports and along the coast.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] With post-war reconstruction and the economic development of the Trente Glorieuses, the city is experiencing a crisis of housing due to the demographic boom, having built on the last vacant land.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Indeed, a 1954 report evaluated 1,000 inhabitant families living in slums and called for 1,500 housing units.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Then out of land *Cité du Casino* in 1957 and the *Cité Fougère* in 1958, then in 1959 all of the *Amont-Quentin*, *Charcot-Spanel* and *Cité Chantereyne* to accommodate the families of the engineers and officers of the Arsenal.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Port Chantereyne and the Mielles lands are reclaimed from the sea, the *Place Divette* and *Boulevard Schuman* are created at the site of the old fairground.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] However, at that time, the change mainly affected nearby villages that formed an agglomeration in less than forty years.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Octeville, a dispersed habitat until the 18th century, and urbanised during the work of the port around a central street, saw the housing estate of the Provinces settle on the heights of la Fauconniere and triple its population in 20 years.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Several estates also emerging at Tourlaville, La Glacerie, Querquerville and Equeurdreville, amending the physiognomy of a suburb which densified.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] This urbanisation resulted in the dilution of the geographic and sociological boundaries of the agglomeration resulting in the creation in 1970 of the urban community until the merger of Cherbourg and Octeville in 2000.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Following this merger, a plan of urban renewal named "Between Land and Sea" was launched in 2002 on the quarters of Bassins, of the Amont-Quentin and the Provinces to homogenise the territory of the newly amalgamated city.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The Bassins quarter, released by the channelling of the Divette and the filling of the retaining channel, is expected to profoundly transform the commercial landscape of the city, carried by the construction of a new shopping centre and the renovation of downtown.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] On the heights, seven HLM tower blocks are intended for demolition to improve social housing.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] A 3-star hotel and the relocation of the casino is also planned.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] At *Avenue Carnot*, the former Grouard warehouses must leave room for parking and a place through from the wharf from the *Quai de l'Entrepôt* to the Pasteur Hospital, to 180 dwellings by Presqu'île habitat and ADIM (Vinci company) then 100 extra in a second round of development.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Since 1996, Cherbourg-Octeville is covered by a sensitive urban zone on the expanded area of the Provinces.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The construction of the dam and the military port has brought an important flow of workers and soldiers.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Cherbourg and Octeville have seen their populations quadruple in a century.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Cherbourg had 43,000 inhabitants at the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] During this century, Cherbourg lost some 15,000 inhabitants, while Octeville grew continuously, with an explosion in the 1960s and 1970s, during the construction of the housing estates.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] According to estimates from INSEE for 2018, Cherbourg-Octeville has 35,545 inhabitants.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] It is the largest city of the Manche department, and second of Lower Normandy (after Caen), surpassing Alençon, which had been second before the amalgamation.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Cherbourg concentrated 7.7% of the departmental population, twice as much as the prefecture, Saint-Lô, while the agglomeration represents 17% and the urban area 23.5%.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The depopulation of the city-centre of the agglomeration was one of the main topics of the campaign for the municipal elections of 2008.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] In addition to the battle of figures on the number of lost inhabitants, the three candidates, Bernard Cazeneuve (PS), Jean Lemière (UMP) and Hervé Corbin (dissident UMP) indicated a new interest in this problem.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The urbanisation of the Grimesnil/Monturbet zone, provided for the coming years, should logically bring extra population, although no one knows if it will be enough to stop the demographic bleeding.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Demographic changes of Cherbourg and Octeville compared, before their merger.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Today, the neighbouring communes of the metropolitan area (Martinvast, Nouainville, Tonneville, Bretteville, etc.) are experiencing a demographic boost: The framework of life, rural and peaceful, in no way prevents the inhabitants from taking advantage of the infrastructure of the urban community.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] This problem, which is found in many French towns of this size, has led to the constitution of a *Pays du Cotentin*, the urban community who wish to so participate financially in the rich Community of communes of Les Pieux and the Community of communes of La Hague.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Since the merger between Cherbourg and Octeville, in February 2000, the inhabitants are officially called *Cherbourgeois-Octevillais*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Before, the inhabitants of Cherbourg was called the *Cherbourgeois* and those of Octeville were the *Octevillais*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] It is likely that, with the merger, the latter disappears gradually in favour of *Cherbourgeois*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] This would be similar to *Équeurdrevillais* (or sometimes *Équeurdrais*) for the nearby of Équeurdreville-Hainneville, which merged communes in 1965.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Cherbourg and Octeville have two different profiles.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The first is the city centre, with varied habitat, the other a commune in suburbs, built quickly from the 1960s.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The second half of the 19th century saw the creation of many English-style gardens.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The first was due to Joseph Cachin created while he was responsible for the construction of the port, a private garden and a pond near the Divette, instead of the current railway line leading to the station.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The temperate oceanic climate favours the naturalisation of southern and exotic plants such as palm trees, brought back by many Cherbourg sailors and explorers.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Then, under the Third Republic, public gardens opened.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] A private garden, the Botanical Garden of the Roche Fauconnière, is also listed in the inventory of Historic Monuments since 29 December 1978.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Established in 1873, it was embellished over generations by the Favier family.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The commune also has allotments, managed by associations: Vallon Sauvage, Fourches, Roquettes, Saint Sauveur and Redoute, which gives free land to its members.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] In 2007, the municipality was awarded four flowers in the competition of flowery towns and villages.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The beautification policy, which dates from 1995, resulted in obtaining a first flower, followed by a second in 2000 and third in 2002.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] At the instigation of Colbert, the guild of drapers was founded on 16 April 1668, the manufacture of cloth produced two thousand pieces per year.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Two years earlier, Colbert had also promoted the introduction of the glass factory in the forest of Tourlaville.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] In the 18th century, the economic resources came mainly through maritime trade, the preparation of cured meats and the harbour and breakwater works, plus a moribund textile industry.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] On the eve of the French Revolution, salt was imported from Le Croisic along with British grain, and Littry coal.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Exports were mainly to Britain (sheets and clothes) and the West Indies (cattle and mules, fat and salted butter, salted meats, cod, linens and canvas), but also to Le Havre and La Rochelle for wood and coal.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Lawful or otherwise exchanges also took place with the Channel Islands (tanbark, grain and wool).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Cherbourg shipowners were absent from significant fishing, including that of cod on the banks of Newfoundland, which was a specialty of Granville.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] 361 workers (1764) and 69 skilled workers (1778) of the factory annually produced (1760) 2,000 fine linens in green and white strip.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Cherbourg also had seven producers of starch.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Opened in 1793 at the location of the current Lawton-Collins Wharf, the arsenal was moved in 1803 on a decision by Napoleon, within the project of the military port.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Sailing ships were built, the first, the brig *La Colombe*, was launched on 27 September 1797, and then screw-propelled vessels up to the end of the 19th century.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] From 1898, the Arsenal specialised in the construction of submarines.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The first were *Le Morse* and *Le Narval*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Since then, more than 91 vessels have been built there.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] At the beginning of the 20th century, Cherbourg was primarily a military port.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] At this time the port embraced the transatlantic epic.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Cherbourg's industry was then specialised in shipbuilding, as well as in lace-making and the manufacture of rope.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The late 19th century also saw Cherbourg develop an aviation industry, through the company of Félix du Temple, taken over in 1938 by Félix Amiot, another aviation pioneer for the aerospace company of Normandy.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Gradually, workers developed a particular skill in metalwork, both for the submarines of the Arsenal, for aircraft and ships of the Amiot shipyards or Babcock-Wilcox boilers.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] In 1916, Nestlé introduced its first French factory in Cherbourg.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The 1960s saw a revival of the local economy through the increase in the female workforce and the decline of agricultural employment in favour of diversification of jobs and a high-tech industry.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] In 1960, under the leadership of Mayor Jacques Hébert, Hortson was established in the Maupas quarter.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] One hundred employees manufactured projectors and film cameras, particularly for the ORTF and Russian television.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Redeemed, the factory specialised under the name of Thomson-CSF audiovisual in surveillance and medical cameras, then in the production of electronic circuits of computer terminals on behalf of Constructions Mécaniques de Normandie and the Arsenal.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] For a decade, the electronic workshop expanded, adding a production line for mobile television relays, and a workshop for mechanical surface treatment.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] As part of the internal restructuring of Alcatel, the site, which has 300 employees, was sold in 2002 to Sanmina-SCI, which ceased its activity in March 2008.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The *Compagnie industrielle des télécommunications* (CIT), merged the following decade with Alcatel, it also opened an assembly plant for electronic telephone exchanges, at Querqueville in the 1960s.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Cherbourg is also the cradle of the Halley family and society, which became Promodès in the 1960s (Continent hypermarkets, Champion supermarkets).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] In 1999, Promodès merged with Carrefour.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The old buildings of Halley House became the technical centre of the Cachin vocational school, on *Avenue Aristide-Briand*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] In 1999, the economically active population of Cherbourg and Octeville was 18,671 inhabitants in a total population of 42,288 inhabitants.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Cherbourg-Octeville supports an unemployment rate (19.6% in 1999), double that of its job base (9.3% in 2006, a decrease of 1.1% in one year) which itself has the highest unemployment of the basins of employment of the department.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] At 31 December 2004, there were 3,700 jobseekers.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Therefore, the annual average household income is lower than the national average (€13,730 for the city, compared with €15,027 in France) despite an average monthly salary (€1,590 in 2001) highest job growth of the department and higher than that of Caen-Bayeux (€1,550).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Cherbourg is the seat of the Chamber of Commerce and Industry of Cherbourg-Cotentin particularly manages the airport, the fishing ports of Cherbourg and the trade, and, together with the Chamber of Commerce and Industry of Centre and Sud-Manche, the FIM group training organisation.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The Cherbourg economy derives a large part of its activities from its maritime position.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Cherbourg indeed has four ports: A military port, a fishing port, a port of commerce (passenger traffic and cross-border goods) and a marina.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Weakened since the 1990s, the commercial port sees the transit of 110,000 trucks to or from Ireland and Great Britain.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] In recent years, the cross-Channel passenger traffic has declined, with competition from Caen-Ouistreham and the Pas-de-Calais.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The withdrawal of the P&O company, which served Poole and Southampton, has left two companies with cross-Channel links: Brittany Ferries to Portsmouth and Poole and Irish Ferries to Rosslare (Ireland).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] In the first eleven months of 2007 compared with the same period of 2006, passenger traffic declined by 3.84% to 750,000 units, while freight fell 4.43% with 87,000 trucks landed.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] For comparison, the port had 1.7 million passengers and 138,000 trucks in 1995.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Property, with the Port of Caen-Ouistreham, of the joint association Ports Norman Associates, involving the Regional Council of Lower Normandy and the Departmental Councils of Manche and Calvados, port trade is managed by a joint company of the Chamber of commerce and Louis Dreyfus Armateurs.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The construction of a terminal dedicated to the traffic of coal from South America and destined for the United Kingdom will put an end to the haemorrhage of the activity of the port.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The fishing industry is affected by the crisis affecting the entire industry, and the port has seen its fleet decline.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Cherbourg was the first French marina by number of visitors in 2007, having 10,117 boats for 28,713 overnight stays in 2007, and the total impact estimated at €4 million for the Cherbourg agglomeration.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] A tradition of local industry, shipbuilding is based on the two pillars of the DCNS Cherbourg for submarines and Constructions Mécaniques de Normandie (CMN), famous for their speedboats.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] This sector has been widely restructured over the past twenty years.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The military arsenal saw the end of the construction of the *Redoutable*-class submarines and expanded its customer base, until then exclusively of the Navy, prior to being privatised in 2007.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] With diesel *Agosta* submarines, developed since 1994 for Pakistan, and the *Scorpène*, in collaboration with the shipyards of Cartagena, sold to Malaysia, Chile and India, 25% of the total turnover of the establishment is of foreign origin.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Partnerships with Pakistan and India have concluded to make the construction term at home.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The CMN, which employed 1,200 people at the beginning of the 1980s, modernised and automated, and now has 500 employees.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The company diversified into large luxury yachts, without abandoning the military market, and has signed such contracts with the United Arab Emirates and Qatar through the Franco-Lebanese businessman Iskandar Safa, owner since 1992.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] While these two military companies have experienced reductions in loads (the number of jobs at the Arsenal increased from 6,000 including 1,000 subcontracted, in 1988, to 2,600 including 500 subcontractors), and the companies have repositioned in the nautical industry.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] JMV Industries, a subsidiary of CMN with 100 employees, built racing yachts.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Originally hosted by CMN to build aluminium hulls designed by James Ébénistes (Saint-Laurent-de-Cuves), Allures Yachting has specialised in cruising sailboats.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The Allais shipyard, of Dieppe, has established a subsidiary, ICAN, dedicated to civilian boats and pleasure craft.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] At Saint-Vaast-la-Hougue, Facnor has become a global specialist of sailing reels.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The Navy employs nearly 3,000 officials in the agglomeration, especially in the context of administration (maritime prefecture), maritime safety (customs, CROSS, Abeille), logistical support of the French Navy and foreign passage, and of training.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Metallurgy has long represented a large source of employment in the agglomeration.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Around the Arsenal and its boilermakers, several metalworking and mechanical industries were formed from the early 1900s.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] This is the case of the oldest business the city, the Simon Brothers company, founded in 1856, which went from being a mechanical workshop to a steam agricultural machinery manufacturer and then to an agribusiness in a half a century.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Manufacturing guns in 1870 and 1939, the company became a world leader in churns and mixers for the butter industry.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Similarly, the Babcock boiler manufacturer was implanted in Cherbourg in the interwar period and closed its doors after a protracted labour dispute, in 1979.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Later, the UIE began business in Cherbourg in 1973, for the construction of oil platforms, but closed in 1985.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The food industry, essential in Lower Normandy, is not absent from the employment pool.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] A farm raising salmon in the harbour, abattoirs handling farmed livestock of Nord-Cotentin, and several processing companies exist.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The Simon Brothers (50 employees) have supplied equipment for the cider and dairy industries for more than a century.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Alcatel had two units in the 1980s, one in Cherbourg, then Tourlaville (formerly Thomson-CSF) the other in Querqueville (Alcatel CIT).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Both, regarded as flagships of the group, specialised respectively in microwave and electronic telephone exchanges.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] However, Alcatel decided to close the Querqueville factory in 1997, Codifur then took over part of the business with hundreds of employees.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] In 2002, it also offloaded the Tourlaville unit to Sanmina-SCI, which relocated its production six years later.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Codifur resumed the after-sales service business of Alcatel, or 5% of the initial activity, and a few dozen employees.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Socoval, a manufacturer of menswear of the Cantoni Group from Italy, is the last textile factory of the Cotentin and employs about 100 employees, since the social plan of 2001, which resulted in the loss of about 40 employees.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Economic partners now rely on the "mastery of atmosphere", i.e. the control of contamination from industrial processes, through the Cherbourg-Normandy technopole created in 2001.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Having experience of work involving nuclear risk, it wants to transfer these skills to the food, electronics and pharmaceutical industries.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Two courses have been designed for this purpose: A BTS in nuclear maintenance at the Lycee Tocqueville and a DESS in mastery of atmosphere at the Cherbourg School of Engineering.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Trade employs nearly 1,400 people in the city centre, but the decline in cross-Channel traffic has caused a big shortfall, exacerbated by the fragile local economy.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Although downtown Cherbourg is the main commercial centre of the agglomeration, with 340 establishments, its dominance is lower in the urban community, when compared to Caen towards its agglomeration.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Indeed, Cherbourg focuses 35% of commercial activities and 45% of retail trade in the agglomeration, against 40% and 55% for the centre of Caen respectively, particularly two-thirds of the human equipment stores against 90% in Lower Normandy's capital.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Grocery chains, equipment and home appliances have left the city centre for out-of-town shopping centres.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The number of fast food outlets doubled between 1995 and 2005, while the strength of the traditional catering has stagnated.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Cherbourg-Octeville, the largest city of the department, is the main centre for administration and services for the Cotentin.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Health is an important provider of jobs with the Pasteur hospital (470 beds, second of Lower Normandy, merged since 2006 with the Hospital of Valognes) and the Cotentin Polyclinic.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The same goes for the education sector with four public and four private schools, a marine high school and aquaculture, a university campus and several graduate schools.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The branches of public enterprises are also located there (EDF, with 120 officers and SNCF, with 50 officers).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Public employment represents an important part with, in addition to the hospital and schools, municipal and community staff.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Business service companies are also present in computer science (Euriware, 85 employees), cleanliness (Onet, 240 employees, and Sin&Stes, 100 employees) and advertising (Adrexo, 50 employees).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Cherbourg-Octeville hosts the headquarters of France Bleu Cotentin public radio, and the departmental daily *La Presse de la Manche* (120 employees with his CES press), successor to the Libération de *Cherbourg-Éclair*, and subsidiary of the Groupe SIPA - Ouest-France since 1990.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] France 3 Normandie boasts a local editorial office in the city; Cherbourg's edition of *La Manche libre* covers the agglomeration, La Hague and the Val de Saire; local television 5050 TV has installed its headquarters and its main studio in the area.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Jobs in the construction sector are divided between Faucillion (80 employees), Eiffage (75 employees) and Colas (60 employees).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Since its opening, the *Cité de la Mer* is the tourist engine of Nord-Cotentin.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The cruise terminal also attracts liners each year.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The marina of 1,500 spaces is the first French port of call (11,000 per year).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The capacity of the city was, as of 1 January 2007, 15 hotels and 429 rooms.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The casino, owned by the Cogit Group is the 109th in France, with a turnover of €6.7 million.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] In 2010, the commune of Cherbourg-Octeville was awarded a 3-star equivalent "Ville Internet" label and was upgraded to a 4-star equivalent rating in 2012.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The city has the central office of two cantons: Canton of Cherbourg-Octeville-1 (to the west) and Cherbourg-Octeville-2 (in the east, which also includes the town of La Glacerie).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Departmental advisors are the Socialists Frédéric Bastian, Anna Pic, Karine Duval and Sébastien Fagnen.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The arrondissement of Cherbourg has 189 municipalities and 190,363 inhabitants.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The sub-prefect is Jacques Troncy, former sub-prefect of Montbéliard, appointed 17 March 2014.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Since 1986, the fifth constituency of Manche, known as Cherbourg, covered the three cantons of Cherbourg-Octeville, and those of Equeurdreville-Hainneville, Saint-Pierre-Église and Tourlaville.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] In the context of the legislative redistricting of 2010, the two cantons of Beaumont-Hague and Quettehou integrated the constituency of Cherbourg-Octeville, becoming the 4th constituency.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Despite this redistribution often perceived as advantageous for the right, the outgoing Socialist deputy of the 5th constituency, Bernard Cazeneuve, was re-elected in the first round with 55% of the vote.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Cherbourg-Octeville also has the headquarters of the maritime prefecture of the English Channel and the North Sea, whose authority extends from the Bay of Mont Saint-Michel to the Belgian border.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The maritime prefect is the Vice Admiral of the Squadron, Bruno Nielly.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The maritime quarter of Cherbourg (initials: CH) is restricted to the limits of the department.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The postal codes from prior to the merger of 2000 have been preserved: 50130 for addresses of the former territory of Octeville, 50100 for Cherbourg.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Cherbourg is historically, with the Arsenal and the port, the main focus of labour and trades unions of the department of Manche.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] However, the Cherbourg workers do not lean towards radical or revolutionary movements, nor to yellow unionism, traditionally preferring the reformist tendencies.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] These choices are reflected politically into a strong center-left anchor, dominated by Socialist-radicals and independent Socialists, before whom the SFIO and the Socialist Party are not imposed.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Since the Liberation, with the exception of a Gaullist period of 18 years with Jacques Hébert following René Schmitt's death, the city of Cherbourg has voted in favour Socialist forces.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Similarly, the right won the town hall of Octeville in 1989, for a term, by the division of the left.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Since the redrawing of the electoral district of Cherbourg in 1986, covering the urban population of the agglomeration and the rural district of the Canton of Saint-Pierre-Église, the left-right alternation is the rule in every legislative election.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] With the merging of the municipal councils of Cherbourg and Octeville on 1 March 2000, Jean-Pierre Godefroy (PS), the Mayor of Cherbourg, took the helm of the new administration, and Bernard Cazeneuve (PS), Mayor of Octeville, became the first Deputy.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Bernard Cazeneuve was elected Mayor of Cherbourg-Octeville during the 2001 municipal election, and re-elected in March 2008 with 66.82% of the vote.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Appointed Minister Delegate for European Affairs in May 2012, he gave way to Jean-Michel Houllegatte the following month.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The latter was re-elected following the victory of his list with 51.81% at the second round of the 2014 municipal election.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The municipal council is composed of 39 members including the mayor and eleven assistants.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Thirty Councillors represent a leftist majority, nine represent the opposition.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Personnel expenses exceeded half (60%) of operating expenses.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Almost all of the resources were fuelled by grants (49%) and tax (44%).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Of the seven budgets of the municipal mandate (2001-2007), this budget increased overall by 22% (43% for investments, 15% for operation).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The investment budget is included in the multiannual programme "Unite the city" (2003-2007), presented in December 2002 by Bernard Cazeneuve.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] It sees a transformation of the newly amalgamated city through refurbishment of the pool and Port Chantereyne, development of the Bassins zone, filling the retaining channel, and the construction of the sailing school.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] It is mainly financed by borrowing, increasing the debt of the city (the charges multiplied by two-thirds between 2002 and 2007), lower than the average per capita of the stratum.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Louis XVI removed the viscountcy of Cherbourg by edict in November 1771, and transferred the rights of justice to the Bailiwick of Valognes.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] In 1785, a sub-delegation was created, however it was smaller than the Viscountcy, essentially covering La Hague, as far as Héauville and included Helleville, Tourlaville, and Bretteville, Digosville and Martinvast, and always under the authority of the electoral district of Valognes.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Cherbourg became a town and district in January 1790, seat of a justice of the peace and a civil and criminal court.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] Under the Directory, they were replaced by a simple police court, attended by a justice of the peace, and a police correctional court.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The correctional court closed after the Act of 17 February 1800 and Cherbourg was made a town and township of the Arrondissement of Valognes.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] After his arrival in the city, Napoleon established a Court of first instance by the Decree of 19 July 1811.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] The city is today one of the three main judicial hubs of Manche, along with Coutances and Avranches.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] A remand prison is located in the city centre, behind the buildings of the court.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p02] As a result of the justice reform presented in 2007 by Rachida Dati, the jurisdiction of the Court of Valognes will be integrated to that of Cherbourg.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Two ZEP have been defined, one being on Cherbourg territory in the Quarter of Maupas, the other straddling Cherbourg and Octeville, in the quarter of the Provinces.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Pasteur hospital houses the Institute of training in nursing of Cherbourg-Octeville.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Institute of the Film Industry of Normandy is installed as a result of the International School of Audiovisual Creation and Realisation (EICAR) on the site of the former maritime hospital.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The town also hosts the National Institute of Science and Technology of the Sea (Intechmer), Tourlaville.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The first horse race organised in Normandy took place in Cherbourg in September 1836 on the (now gone) beachfront along the *boulevard maritime*, at the initiative of Éphrem Houël, the officer of the stud.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The races settled in 1931 on the Lande Saint-Gabriel Racecourse in Tourlaville, the work of René Levavasseur, and the Hippodrome de La Glacerie from 1990.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] In football, AS Cherbourg Football, after decades at the national level, is changing, as a result of bad sports results and financial problems, since 2014 in the Ligue de Basse-Normandie de football, equivalent to the 6th division, and is based at the Maurice-Postaire stadium.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The club has also two other senior male teams in the League of Lower Normandy.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Association sportive Amont-Quentin, which had two district teams until June 2013, had to cease its activities.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Octeville Hague Sport, which was developing its teams in 2013–2014, was unable to present any team for the 2014–2015 season.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] In cycling, Cherbourg has been a city of arrival for the Tour de France on sixteen occasions: 1911 to 1914 (four consecutive years), from 1919 to 1929 (eleven consecutive years), and finally in 1986.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The second stage of the 2016 Tour de France finishes at Cherbourg.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Cherbourg regularly hosts stages of sailing competitions such as the Solitaire du Figaro, the Course de l'Europe, the Challenge Mondial Assistance, the Tour de France à la voile, and the Tall Ships' Race.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Challenger La Manche is a professional tennis tournament ($50,000 plus accommodation) held annually in Cherbourg since 1994.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] In ice hockey, NC'HOP (Nord Cotentin Hockey Plus, the *Cherbourg Vikings*) was based in the city.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The team was the successor to CHOC (Cherbourg Hockey Club), who played in FFHG Division 1 until filing for bankruptcy in 1996.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] AS Cherbourg men's basketball team plays in National 2 and the women's team in the Prenational league.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Jeunesse sportive de Cherbourg has a male handball team in Pro D2 and a women's team in Nationale 3 (agreement with Tourlaville).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The club has also implemented a structured training programme for young people, from the 2009/2010 season, around a partnership with colleges of the city.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Gros Hêtre medicalised residence for elderly (a branch of the public hospital in the Cotentin) and, since 1999, the Jean-Brüder Community Health Centre are located on the territory of Octeville.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] In 1859, following the Imperial visit, the State decided upon the construction of a Maritime Hospital of a thousand beds to accommodate the troops in garrison.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Opened on 15 February 1869, it was renamed René-Le-Bas, named after the first doctor who joined the Free Naval Forces and died in 1942 aboard the submarine *Surcouf*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] It was closed in 2002 and renovated as a university campus.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] To this date, it is merged to the deanery of La Hague, to become the Deanery of Cherbourg-Hague, therefore adding the parishes covering the Community of communes of La Hague and of Les Pieux.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Jean-XXIII parish unites Cherbourg and La Glacerie, with the Cherbourg churches of La Trinité (long only parish church), Notre-Dame-du-Roule, Notre-Dame-du-Vœu, St-Jean-des-Carrières and Saint-Clément.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The parish of Saint-Sauveur of Octeville, which also covers Nouainville has three sites in the commune: Saint-Martin, the historic site, Saint-Pierre-Saint-Paul, at Provinces, and the Chapel of Saint-Barthélemy.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Protestants have a temple of the Reformed Church (since 1835, rebuilt after the war in 1964), and a Pentecostal Evangelical church affiliated with the Assemblies of God.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Evangelical Baptist Church has been present since 1985 in the agglomeration and is currently located in Tourlaville.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Muslim community then opened three mosques (the Mosque of Omar in Octeville, the Mosque de la Gare, on the *Avenue de Normandie*, and then the Turkish mosque, on the *Boulevard de l’Atlantique*).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, Parish of Cherbourg, has its chapel on the *Rue du Commerce*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The work of the seawall and the military port in Cherbourg led many soldiers and engineers, for whom this step was often an important moment in their career.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Thus, Charles François Dumouriez (1739–1823), Governor of Cherbourg who was responsible for the first work, at the dawn of the French Revolution, Joseph Cachin (1757–1825), engineer assigned by Napoleon to the general direction of the maritime work of Cherbourg in 1804.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] For twenty years, he realised the improvement of the commercial port, and the digging of the docks of the military port, constituting the New Arsenal.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Henri Rieunier (1833–1918) who was twice major of the Navy in Cherbourg (1872/1875) and Louis-Émile Bertin (1840–1924) who lived in Cherbourg from 1863 to 1879, and is buried in the cemetery of La Glacerie.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Charles-Eugène Delaunay (1816–1872), Director of the Paris Observatory, drowned while visiting the harbour.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Among the engineers of the Directorate of construction and naval weapons, included Augustin-Louis Cauchy (1789–1857) and also Maxime Laubeuf.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Under the Ancien Régime, the safeguarding of the Château de Cherbourg was already the task of illustrious figures of the Kingdom, such as Pierre des Essarts, the family of Matignon and Jacques de Callières (d.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] At the origin of the military port, Napoleon (1769–1821), who visited the city in 1811, *"Revient"* in Cherbourg in 1840 during the return of his remains to France, aboard *Belle Poule*, before being taken to Les Invalides.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] A transatlantic port of the 20th century, Cherbourg saw Hollywood stars arrive, such as Charlie Chaplin, who organised his disembarkation in 1952 to a press conference in the *gare maritime*, critical of the McCarthyist America that he left.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The port saw a lot of famous people, including businessman Benjamin Guggenheim (1865–1912) for his fatal voyage on the Titanic.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Cinema then gave Cherbourg another lasting reputation, through the images of Jacques Demy (1931–1990) and music by Michel Legrand (1932-2019), in *The Umbrellas of Cherbourg*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Earlier, Frida Boccara (1940–1996), knew great success in 1961 with her song *Cherbourg avait raison*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The letters were not left with academician Georges Grente (1872–1959), superior of the Saint-Paul Institute, and Ernest Psichari (1883–1914), soldier and writer, whose garrison stay in Cherbourg in 1914 with the 2nd colonial artillery regiment inspires *L'Appel des armes*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] With Caen, Cherbourg-Octeville is the main cultural centre of Lower Normandy.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The city is the seat of several learned societies, including the National Academic Society of Cherbourg founded in 1755, National Society of Natural Sciences and Mathematics of Cherbourg formed in 1851, and the Artistic and Industrial society of Cherbourg, incorporated in 1871.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The creation and dissemination of the performing arts are ensured by the *Trident*, national stage of Italian theatre, the theatre of Octeville and the *Vox*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Amateur theatre is celebrated by *Les Téméraires*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The *vocation prioritaire du Centre régional des arts du cirque* [Priority Mission of the Regional Centre of Circus Arts] (CRAC) of La Brèche, opened in October 2006, is the residence of circus troops, but instead also offers programming for the public.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] CRAC participates in the festival of street arts, *Charivarue*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] In addition, the provision of artistic education is rich, with the Film Industry Institute of Normandy, the school of fine arts and the municipal music school, labelled as a conservatory for communal influence, which has 800 registrants.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] However, the city lacks a large capacity venue, the theatre can accommodate only 700 spectators.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] After the bitter failure of *Cherbourg-Land*, this problem has not been resolved at the level of the Cotentin.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Great Hall of the Cité de la Mer, with a space for over 6,000 people, has hosted several concerts, but it is primarily dedicated to the organisation of fairs and exhibitions.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Today, the main welcoming complex of large-scale concerts is the Jean-Jaurès Centre of Équeurdreville-Hainneville.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Octeville has retained its patronal festival, the Sainte-Échelle, with holiday fair and parades.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Cherbourg restarted its carnival in the 1980s, heir of the Confrérie des Conards, similar to that of Rouen and Évreux.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] It is also the headquarters of the National Society of Natural Sciences and Mathematics of Cherbourg.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Thomas-Henry Fine Arts Museum, named after its first patron, was inaugurated in 1835 and is now the third collection of Normandy with 300 paintings and sculptures from the 15th to the 20th century.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Located in the cultural centre, at the back of the theatre, it presents paintings by French, Flemish, Spanish and Italian artists, as well as sculptures.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Presentations of works by Fra Angelico, Simon Vouet, Camille Claudel, and one of the largest collections of works by Jean-François Millet, as well as paintings by Guillaume Fouace native of Réville or the Navy painters.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Sculptures by Armand Le Véel are also included.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Museum of the War and the Liberation, the first of its kind when it was inaugurated by René Coty on 6 June 1954, traces the daily life of Cherbourg civilians during the Occupation and the course of the Liberation of Cotentin, particularly the Battle of Cherbourg.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] It is installed in the Fort du Roule, centrepiece of the defence of Cherbourg taken by the Americans on 25 June 1944 .
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Cité de la Mer, is a large museum devoted to scientific and historical aspects of maritime subjects.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Dedicated to oceanographic exploration, it is a complex installed since 2003 in a part of the remains of the old transatlantic station.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] It offers giant aquariums, a collection of underwater vehicles, such as those of COMEX, the bathyscaphe *Archimède* and *Redoutable*, the first French SSBN built in Cherbourg, fully open to the public.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The *Point du jour*, a unique contemporary art centre in France, dedicated to photography, was inaugurated in the Bassin zone in November 2008.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Jacques Prévert Municipal Library, founded in 1831 and opened in 1832, holds the second largest collection in the region, after that of Caen.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] It also has a Norman fonds, an old fonds devoted to botany and another to travel.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Housed in a wing of the City Hall in 1855, and then at 9 *Rue Thiers* (*Rue Talluau*) from 1896, the library moved into the cultural centre in June 1981, taking the name of Jacques Prévert, who had died four years earlier in La Hague.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The library also participates in the *Normannia* project of the Norman digital library.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The former barracks of the Abbey, dating back to the start of the works of the large dam in 18th-century, has housed one of the five regional centres of history of the National Navy, alongside Brest, Lorient, Rochefort and Toulon, since 1970.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The archives of the maritime district of the Channel and the North Sea are grouped here, and the library of the Navy founded in 1836 in Cherbourg and specialising in maritime history with its 23,000 works.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Each year, a network of writing workshops are organised in the metropolitan area, the *Mercurielles*, and the Festival of the Book and of Youth Comic Books (since 1987).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Biennial of the 9th Art exhibits the works of comic cartoonists (Enki Bilal in 2002, François Schuiten and Benoît Peeters in 2004, André Juillard in 2006, and Loustal in 2008).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Cherbourg-Octeville is the seat of two publishing houses, *Isoète* founded in 1985 and *Le Point du jour* established in 1996.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The cinema occupies a significant place in the life of Cherbourg.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Many classics of French cinema have been filmed there, such as *La Marie du port* directed by Marcel Carné and starring Jean Gabin.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] In 1981, Claude Miller also located the action film *Garde à Vue* there, though shot in the studio.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] However, the most emblematic is undoubtedly *The Umbrellas of Cherbourg* directed by Jacques Demy, a story about Madame Emery and her 17-year-old daughter Geneviève (Catherine Deneuve) who sell umbrellas at their tiny boutique.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The film was shot in the summer of 1963, and still contributes to the international renown of the city.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Yet long before, at the time of the splendor of the transatlantic liners, Cherbourg was a port of arrival, departure or transit for many stars, including Charlie Chaplin and Burt Lancaster.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The city was also birthplace of the filmmaker Jean-Charles Tacchella and the actor Jean Marais.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Festival of cinemas of Ireland and Great Britain, the Cinemovida (festival of the cinema of Spain and Latin America), and Images d'Outre-Rhin (German cinema), as well as Cin'étoiles, screenings of films outdoors in July, animate the local cultural life.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] In 2003, the EICAR film school was located in the old buildings of the marine hospital.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The city has a fleet of 17 permanent cinema rooms, distributed over two sites, including one labelled as *Art et essai* (Revival house).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The cinema had 90,000 admissions in 2006.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The damaged façade of the old cafe of the Grand balcon, which then became *Le Central* cinema, is in the style of the Second Empire, with caryatids and garlands of flowers.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Opened in 2003 near the *boulevard maritime* with 2,557 seats; 400,000 admissions in 2006.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The historic cinema operated by Pathé, located on the *Rue de la Paix*, it was bought in the 1990s by the municipality and no longer welcomes any more than rare events.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Lecoq, representing Aeolus and Vulcan, were distinguished in 2006 by the label "20th century heritage" of the Ministry of Culture.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Several cinemas have disappeared, such as the *Eldorado* (destroyed, *Place de la Republique*), the *Eden* (*Rue Cachin*), the *Vox* (former patronage room which became a second room of Le Trident (theatre)), and the *Saint-Joseph* (*Rue des Ormes*), etc.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Cherbourg population spoke *le haguais*, a variant of Cotentinais Norman, while having some specifics regarding the pronunciation of certain words.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] In Cotentinais Norman, Cherbourg is called *Tchidbouo* [tʃidbwu:] and Octeville, *Otteville* [ɔtvil].
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Their inhabitants are the *Tchidbouorqŭais* and the *Ottevillais* [tʃidbwuʁtʃje:] and [ɔtvile:].
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] While French was necessary in Rouen in the 19th century, Norman remained widely used from Cherbourg to Caen, up to the First World War.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Alfred Rossel was the leading local figure of the dialect authors of the 19th century.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] He published his *Chansonnettes normandes*, among which *Sus la mé* became an anthem of the Cotentin Peninsula.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] At that time, Jean Fleury was critical of its approximate spelling and poor mastery of the language.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Various actors are now trying to promote the local use of the Norman.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Alfred Rossel society makes live folklore and language.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] *Le Boué-jaun* a Cherbourg-based magazine, published his texts in Norman, and one of three popular Norman universities is based here.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The so-called Demoiselles de Cherbourg are small lobsters.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Cherbourg is also located near three oyster areas (Blainville, Saint-Vaast and Isigny).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The most traditional preparation is the matelote.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Alexandre Dumas also presented the recipe of the *"queue de merlan à la mode de Cherbourg "* [tail of whiting in the Cherbourg manner], with butter and oysters.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] From 1464, the bakers of Cherbourg held Royal permission to develop their breads based on seawater, thus avoiding paying for the salt and the *gabelle* [salt tax].
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] On the occasion of the visit of Napoleon, they would have created folded bread, country bread ball, oval, which is folded back on itself to be cooked, thus offering a tighter bicorn-shaped sandwich which came to be called *"pain Napoléon"* [Napoleon bread].
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The agglomeration is located in the AOC areas of the Pont-l'Évêque and of the Camembert of Normandy as well as being partially within the Calvados, Pommeau de Normandie and the cider of Normandy.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] It also benefits from the IGP of the cider of Normandy, Normandy pork and Normandy poultry.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] More broadly, the kitchen of Nord-Cotentin is that of Normandy, in which dairy products (butter, cream, milk, cheese, etc.) and apples (as fruit or alcohol) dominate.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Since 2010, the restaurant *le Pily*, of the Valognes restaurateur Pierre Marion, holds a star in the Michelin Guide.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Italian Theatre is one of the last Italian theatres built in France (1880).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Opened in 1882, it was built on the plans of Charles de Lalande, on the site of the grain market.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The façade pays homage to Molière, Boieldieu and Corneille.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] It has been classified a historical monument since 1984 with its two side returns and corresponding roofing; also classified are the vestibule, the grand staircase, the hall and foyer, as well as the 13 original decorations.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The ceiling is the work of Georges Clairin.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] With three galleries, it accommodates up to 600 spectators.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Mouchel Fountain, named after the patron and director of the journal *Le Phare de la Manche*, stands at the centre of the *Place Général-de-Gaulle*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] A monumental fountain in cast iron, it was created by Louis Eugène Gutelle in 1895.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Hotel Epron de la Horie (named after the Vice Admiral and Marine Minister Jacques Epron de la Horie, owner under the first Empire) or ancient customs is located at the corner of *Rue de Val-de-Saire* and the wharf of the Old Arsenal.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Built in 1781 by Jacques Martin Maurice, "contractor of the King's works" in schist (cover and body of the building) and red brick (window frames), registered as a historical monument since 16 February 1965.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Successively barracks of the Swiss, auxiliary Hospital of the work of the harbour, home of shipowners Richer, Cousin, Despréaux and Lias in the 19th century and a customs house during the interwar period, it is now the headquarters of the Groupe Caisse d'Épargne.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The former Gare Maritime de Cherbourg is the largest French Art Deco monument.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Built by René Levavasseur from 1928 and inaugurated in 1933 by President Lebrun, it could accommodate two ships simultaneously.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Listed as an historical monument in 1989 and 2000, it was redeveloped in 2002 to become an oceanographic complex, the Cité de la Mer, where one can visit the SNLE *Le Redoutable*, and host since December 2006 of a cruise terminal.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] It hosted on 5,400 m2 (58,000 sq ft) the emigrants (third class passengers), mainly from Eastern Europe, who stayed there for an average of 12 days to undergo sanitary and customs controls.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The building thus included a section for infected and a section for disinfected with a capacity of 2,000 people.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Begun in 1920, opened in 1926, it closed eight years later.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Requisitioned under the Occupation and Liberation, it was bought by Félix Amiot to accommodate some of its shipyard employees.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] It has hosted the services of the Chamber of commerce and industry of Cherbourg-Cotentin since 1991.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The central pavilion is included in the inventory of historic monuments since October 2001.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] After restoration by Pierre Bataille of Poclain, they were each placed in 1990 and 1993 on a roundabout, the *Minerva* of Philippe-Laurent Roland, near the Cité de la Mer, the *Themis* of Jean-Antoine Houdon at the foot of the Montagne du Roule.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Carved around 1810, they have been classified as historic monuments since June 1990.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The town hall was built at the beginning of the 19th century; It was enlarged twice, first in 1850 by a south-west wing forming an L-shape with the first building, and then under the Second Empire (salon of the Empress), and reworked after the Liberation.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Inside, a staircase serves the Grand Lounge and the lounge of the Empress, which houses portraits of Napoleon III and Eugénie by Winterhalter, with - between the two – a rotunda room for the paintings of Michel-Adrien Servant recalling the major events in the history of the city.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Since 1858, the Council Chamber contains the 16th century chimney of the abbot's house of the Abbey of Notre-Dame-du-Vœu, purchased by the municipality in 1841 and classified as a historical monument since 1905.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The three lounges and the stairs have been registered since 13 August 2004.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The maritime hospital, a former regional hospital of the armies of René-Le-Bas, built by a decision of Napoleon III and opened 15 February 1869, it was decommissioned in 2000 and rehabilitated as an academic and cultural centre in 2002.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Napoleon III style buildings are surrounded by a large park.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The docks and Port Chantereyne are regularly brought to life by various events: Stopovers of prestigious liners (*Queen Elizabeth 2*, *Queen Mary 2*, etc.), armada, sailing races and such.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The docks were constructed in 1994 with the lighting by Yann Kersalé.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The marina, first French port of call, extends beyond the *Plage Verte*, old beach redeveloped into lawn after the creation of the port.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Recreational and leisure facilities are located here (pool, skating rink, bowling, services for boaters, etc.).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] In the commercial wet dock is the *Jacques-Louise*, the last wooden trawler built in the shipyards of Cherbourg Bellot in 1959, the former Cherbourg Blue Riband, decommissioned in 1991, registered in 1996, then classified as a historic monument in 1999.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] A trawler in oak wood of the Orne, designed for lateral fishing off the coast, it has been open to the public since summer 2004.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Equestrian Statue of Napoleon I faces the basilica, on the *Place Napoléon*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The work of Armand Le Véel, it represents the Emperor contemplating the harbour and the military port.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] On the base, reads an excerpt from the *Memorial of Sainte-Hélène*, dated 15 July 1816: *I had resolved to renew to Cherbourg the wonders of Egypt*, i.e. a pyramid with central fort and a new Lake Moeris, for the outer harbour, dug into the rock.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The statue, erected in 1858 on the occasion of the visit of Napoleon III, recalls the importance of the Emperor in the expansion of Cherbourg.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Around this emblematic monument of the city, registered in August 2006 and classified as an historic monument on 31 January 2008, extends the *Plage verte*, the old artificial beach until the postwar period, which runs along the marina.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The monument of the Duke of Berry, in the *Place de la République*, commemorates the landing of the son of the future Charles X, back in France on the British frigate *Eurotas* on 13 April 1814, after the fall of the Empire.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Completed in 1816, it consists of an obelisk of 25 ft (7.6 m) in pink granite of Flamanville, surmounting a fountain of grey granite, where four bronze lions' heads spew water into a basin dug in the same block.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The bust of Colonel Bricqueville, on the *Quai de Caligny*, was inaugurated on 12 May 1850, in homage to the Colonel of the Imperial Dragons and Bonapartist deputy of Cherbourg who died in 1844.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] This 1.45 m (4.8 ft) bust of Hermes is a bronze of David d'Angers on a 4 ft (1.2 m) column of granite of the architect Lemelle, on which one can read the name of four battles where Bricqueville is illustrated: Wagram, Krasnoi, Antwerp and Versailles.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Two bronze reliefs evoke the military (a sword) and parliamentary (a forum), were melted by the Germans in 1944.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The monument has been listed as an historical monument since August 2006.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The statue of Jean-François Millet, inaugurated in the public garden on 22 September 1892, for the centenary of the First Republic, honours the "painter of peasants", student at the Museum of Cherbourg.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The monument is inscribed since August 2006.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The monument to the dead of the *Surcouf*, inaugurated at the end of the marina pier on 23 September 1951 by General de Gaulle, commemorates the memory of 130 sailors from the Free French Naval Forces submarine, built at Cherbourg and which sank on 18 February 1942 in the Pacific.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Cherbourg Harbour is the largest artificial harbour of the world.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Begun in 1783, the central wall was completed in 1853 and equipped with three forts in 1860.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Built 4 km (2.5 mi) from the coast, the offshore seawall is 3.64 km (2.26 mi) long, with an average width of 100 m (330 ft) at its base and 12 m (39 ft) at its peak, and a height of 27 m (89 ft).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The three sea walls cover over 6 km (3.7 mi) combined.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The fort de l’Île Pelée [fort of Pelée Island], a defensive element to the east of the sea wall, was designed by Ricard and Decaux and built between 1777 and 1784.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] It was named *fort Royal, fort National, fort Imperial*, before taking the name of the island on which it was built.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] It served as a prison during the Revolution.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Fort du Roule (Museum of the War and Liberation) is located on the *Montagne du Roule*.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The location in 1650 of the Chapel of Notre-Dame-de-Protection, abandoned during the Revolution, razed in 1870, this highest point of the city [117 m (384 ft)] welcomed a redoubt to protect the harbour in 1793.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The place of the last fighting in 1940, it was reinforced by the Germans in 1943 with a battery located on the hillside overlooking the harbour, below the fort.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Composed of four casemates for 105 mm (4.1 in) guns and a position for the direction of firing, with several tunnels and access dug into the rock, for the Germans it became the strong point of the *fortresse de Cherbourg* and of the Atlantic Wall.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] On 6 June 1954, René Coty inaugurated the first French Museum of Liberation there.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] At the end of a winding road named *chemin des Résistants* [Path of Resistants], the fort offers a panoramic view of the city and the harbour.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The battery and a part of the German ammunition storage tunnels were classified as a historic monument in 1995, and another part is converted into an underground laboratory for measurement of radioactivity for the school of military application of atomic energy.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Abbey of Notre-Dame-du-Vœu was founded in 1145, on the coast of Équeurdreville, at the *Croûte du Homet*, by Empress Matilda.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Located outside the city walls, it was regularly looted and burned during the incessant Anglo-French battles, then during the Wars of Religion.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Subject to the regime of a commendatory abbot in 1583, it declined until its closure in 1774.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Its lands were annexed in 1778 for the construction of the military port, and it became the residence of the Duke of Harcourt, who sheltered the King in 1786.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The place was then transformed into a hospital, into a prison, and into the Martin des Pallières Barracks for the marine infantry.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The company town of Chantereyne was built in 1928, until its destruction in June 1944.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Bought by the Town Hall in 1961, the Abbey has been slowly restored since 1965.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The smokestack of the Abbey House (16th century) is kept in the council room of the city hall, the west portal of the Church (13th century) is placed in the public garden.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The remains of Martin des Pallières barracks were classified in 1913, then all of the buildings, remains and soil of the abbey, in September 2002.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The grave slab of Guillaume de Margerai, priest of Querqueville, who died in the 1280s, uncovered, has been classified as an historic monument since 1995.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Basilica of Sainte-Trinité, begun in the 11th century at the request of William the Conqueror, remained the only parish church of the city until the 19th century.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The stately church dedicated to Our Lady in the castle was destroyed along with the fortress, in the 17th century.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Trinité was enlarged and transformed significantly in the 13th century, the nave was rebuilt, the choir and the bell tower is recorded from after 1450.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] After a rampage by January 1794, it had added a new square bell tower 26 m (85 ft) in 1828 and restored in neo-flamboyant style in 1865.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Registered as a historical monument since March 1944, Trinité has a rich religious furniture, including a high altar of 1809, a wood pulpit carved by Pierre Fréret (1767), a retable of Armand Fréret (1814) and the great organs by Cavaillé-Coll.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The church of Notre-Dame du Roule was built at the foot of the *Montagne du Roule* between 1832 and 1842 under the leadership of the "poet-Barber" Michel Legoupil and by the subscription of the faithful of the peripheral quarters of Roule which grew, such as the districts of the Vœu and the Polle.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The church of Notre-Dame-du-Vœu, begun in 1850 on subscription of the parishioners and in the Romanesque style due to the scarcity of resources, was erected on a pasture, known as *les briques*, offered by Mr. de Virandeville.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] In 1855, the municipality completes the nave inaugurated in 1852 by a transept and a more ornate choir, and in 1862 the façade and two bell towers.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] A work of 61.5 m (202 ft) in length, the church houses a large organ by Duputel (1885), classified as a historic monument since 1990 and the stained glass windows of 1834, 1858–60 and 1949–58.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Church of Saint-Clément was built within the quarter of the Val-de-Saire, facing the Pasteur hospital, between June 1853 and 1856 by the architect of the city, Geufroy.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] 52 m (171 ft) long, it is of Greco-Roman inspiration, with a porch in the triangular pediment supported by four columns with Doric capitals.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] It houses the altars of the Virgin (1863) by François Fréret and Saint-Clément (1864) by Louis-Victor Fréret, acquired from the Basilica of Sainte-Trinité in 1846, an organ (1881), painting of the twelve apostles (1935) the Rock of Césigné and stained glass (1953) of Mauméjean.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Church of Saint-Pierre and Saint-Paul, on the area of Octeville, was built between 1967 and 1969 while the "grand ensemble" of Provinces was born.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The triangular and irregular modern architecture of Paul Vimond symbolises "the tent of God in among the houses of men", a sacred art inspired by the Second Vatican Council (1962-1965).
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Another Church was built on Octeville during those years: The Church of Sainte-Marie-Madeleine-Postel opened in 1966 in the quarter of Fourches and decommissioned in 1990.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The Church of Saint-Martin of Octeville, dating from the 12th century, is the historic parish church of Octeville which depended on the Abbey of Notre-Dame-du-Vœu.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] Romanesque, it has an octagonal saddleback steeple.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] The nave was remodelled in the 18th century.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p03] A relief depicting the Last Supper has been classified as a historic monument since 1908.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p04] During the Middle Ages, Cherbourg, a stronghold of the Cotentin peninsula, was home to a small garrison for the protection of the fortress.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p04] With the implementation of the harbour and military port, Cherbourg became a port of war at the end of the 18th century, with a large garrison.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p04] In 1798, it had 1,332 men, or a tenth of the population, divided mainly between the barracks of the Abbey, current historical Service of the Navy, which housed 542 men of the 4th brigade and the Maurice Quarter, in the *Hôtel Epron de la Horie*, home to 227 men.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p04] Numbers were brought to 3,000 men for the completion of the work, by a decree of germinal year XI.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p04] During the 20th century, Cherbourg, a strategic point during both world wars, adapted to new threats.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p04] It then hosted a large garrison of the Navy, an artillery regiment and a *Hôpital des Armées* known locally as "marine hospital".
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p04] In the late 1990s and early 2000s, the presence of the army weakened by the transfer of the northern fleet to Brest and the closure of the maritime hospital renamed René-Le-Bas.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p04] Yet Cherbourg remained a base of the first order of the National Navy, as the seat of the Maritime Prefecture of Manche and the North Sea and of the Maritime Gendarmerie grouping of Manche.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p04] The naval base is the homeport of five patrol vessels of the Navy and the coastguard, group of the clearance divers sleeve and its building-base the *Vulcain*, the tug *Abeille Liberté* and various support vessels.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p04] It is also the headquarters of the Operational Training of Surveillance and Territorial Information of Cherbourg (Cherbourg FOSIT) which brings together thirteen semaphores and the lookout of the maritime district.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p04] In addition, a flotilla 35 F Dauphin helicopter is based at Cherbourg – Maupertus Airport.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p04] The operation of the military port is borne by the directions of the Commissioner of the Navy, maritime works and information systems of the Navy, as well as the branch of the support service of the fleet and the military workshop of the Cherbourg fleet.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p04] According to projects, Cherbourg-Octeville would become one of 90 defence bases around 2010.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p04] In a pooling of means and the establishment of support for the armed forces, the city would retain military and civilian activities, and would host new regiments for the army and of the air force to constitute one of the largest bases of defence.
[src:cherbourg/cherbourg-p04] National orders for DCNS could be spread over several years, also reducing human needs there, especially among the subcontractors.
